/** <module> Teacher-facing lesson digest from the vision harvest of the
 *  Illustrative Mathematics 6-8 teacher guides (2026-07-12).
 *
 *  One structured record per lesson: goals, Common Core standards, the exact
 *  computations the lesson contains (with answers, page, and whether the
 *  operand was recovered from a figure a text extractor drops), anticipated
 *  student errors, and the honest developmental boundary. Source-cited; a
 *  cache with provenance, not an authority. Regenerate with
 *  scripts/curriculum/build_digest.py from the vendored vision harvest.
 */
:- module(vision_lesson_digest,
          [ vision_lesson/5,
            vision_lesson_goal/3,
            vision_lesson_purpose/2,
            vision_lesson_standard/3,
            vision_lesson_computation/6,
            vision_lesson_error/4,
            vision_lesson_boundary/2,
            vision_lessons_for_standard/2,
            vision_lesson_digest_summary/2
          ]).

:- discontiguous vision_lesson/5, vision_lesson_goal/3, vision_lesson_purpose/2,
     vision_lesson_standard/3, vision_lesson_computation/6, vision_lesson_error/4,
     vision_lesson_boundary/2.

vision_lesson('IM-G6-U1-L1', 6, 1, 1, "Tiling the Plane").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U1-L1', teacher, "Compare (orally) areas of the shapes that make up a geometric pattern.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U1-L1', teacher, "Comprehend that the word 'area' (orally and in writing) refers to how much of the plane a shape covers.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U1-L1', student, "Let's look at tiling patterns and think about area.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G6-U1-L1', "In the first lesson of the course, students compare the amounts of a plane covered by different shapes and recall what they know about area. The investigations allow students to experience two important ideas that will be made explicit in the next lesson: (1) If two figures can be placed one on top of the other so that they match up exactly, then they have the same area, and (2) The area of a region does not change when the region is decomposed and rearranged.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U1-L1', building_on, '3.G.A').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U1-L1', building_toward, '6.G.A.1').
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U1-L1', "area_equivalence_rhombus_to_triangles", "1 blue rhombus covers the same area as 2 green triangles", 'main_activity_1.2', "61-64", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U1-L1', "polygon_area_by_decomposition", "42 square units", 'practice_problem_5', "70", figure).
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G6-U1-L1', "This lesson establishes area as 'how much of the plane a shape covers' through visual comparison of geometric patterns, not yet through formula or grid-square counting. Students commonly misjudge area by perimeter, size, or visual appearance rather than actual coverage; the lesson breaks this by showing that different shapes (triangles, rhombuses, trapezoids) can cover equal amounts of plane. The main arithmetic reasoning involves discovering shape equivalences (e.g., 1 rhombus = 2 triangles) by working with concrete tiling patterns.").

vision_lesson('IM-G6-U1-L2', 6, 1, 2, "Finding Area by Decomposing and Rearranging").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U1-L2', teacher, "Calculate the area of a region by decomposing it and rearranging the pieces, and explain (orally and in writing) the solution method.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U1-L2', teacher, "Recognize and explain (orally) that if two figures can be placed one on top of the other so that they match up exactly, they must have the same area.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U1-L2', teacher, "Show that area is additive by composing polygons with a given area.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U1-L2', student, "Let's create shapes and find their areas.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G6-U1-L2', "In this lesson, students learn to reason flexibly about two-dimensional figures to find their areas. Students begin by revisiting and refining earlier definitions of \"area\" that can be used for the rest of the unit. Using tangram pieces, students explore three strategies: composing a figure from smaller pieces with known areas, decomposing a figure and adding the areas of its parts, and decomposing and rearranging into a familiar shape. By the end of the lesson, two key principles are explicit: Figures that match exactly have equal areas, and area is additive (the area of a figure is the sum of the areas of all non-overlapping pieces that compose it).").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U1-L2', building_on, '3.MD.C.5.b').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U1-L2', addressing, '6.G.A.1').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U1-L2', building_toward, '6.G.A').
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U1-L2', "square_from_two_small_triangles", "1 square unit", 'Activity 2.3, Question 1', "78-79", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U1-L2', "small_triangle_area", "1/2 square unit", 'Tangram Triangles section, Question 1', "81-82", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U1-L2', "medium_triangle_area", "1 square unit", 'Tangram Triangles section, Question 2', "81-82", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U1-L2', "large_triangle_area", "2 square units", 'Tangram Triangles section, Question 3', "81-82", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U1-L2', "tangram_rectangle_cool_down", "4 square units", 'Activity 2.5, Cool-down', "84-85", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U1-L2', "rectangle_playground_width", "6 meters", 'Practice Problems, Problem 4', "89", text).
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G6-U1-L2', "Area is fundamentally a measure of how many unit squares cover a region without gaps or overlaps—not a count of pieces or a rote formula. Students often confuse the number of pieces in a composite figure with the number of square units, especially when dealing with non-whole-number areas (e.g., a triangle with area 1/2 square unit). The lesson's core work is to establish that decomposing and rearranging preserve area, and that different shapes can be proven equal in area by exact superposition, building an additive reasoning model that precedes and underlies formula-based approaches.").

vision_lesson('IM-G6-U1-L3', 6, 1, 3, "Reasoning to Find Area").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U1-L3', teacher, "Compare and contrast (orally) different strategies for calculating the area of a polygon.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U1-L3', teacher, "Find the area of a polygon by decomposing, rearranging, subtracting, or enclosing shapes, and explain (orally and in writing) the solution method.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U1-L3', teacher, "Include appropriate units (in spoken and written language) when stating the area of a polygon.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U1-L3', student, "Let's decompose and rearrange shapes to find their areas.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G6-U1-L3', "This lesson prompts students to find areas of figures—first on a grid and then without a grid. Students continue to use strategies from earlier explorations to find area: decomposing figures into known shapes, decomposing and rearranging, considering a figure as a familiar shape with missing pieces to subtract, and enclosing a figure to subtract extra pieces. For now, rectangles are the only shapes whose areas students know how to calculate, but the strategies will become more powerful as students' repertoires grow.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U1-L3', building_on, '3.MD.C.7.d').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U1-L3', addressing, '6.G.A.1').
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U1-L3', "find_area_decomposed_rectangles", "24 square units", 'Activity 3.2 / On the Grid, Figure A', "94-95", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U1-L3', "find_area_enclose_subtract", "27 square units", 'Activity 3.2 / On the Grid, Figure B', "94-95", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U1-L3', "find_area_rearrange_triangles", "16 square units", 'Activity 3.2 / On the Grid, Figure C', "94-95", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U1-L3', "find_area_rotated_square_with_triangles", "20 square units", 'Activity 3.2 / On the Grid, Figure D', "95-96", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U1-L3', "find_area_trapezoid_offgrid", "12 square centimeters", 'Activity 3.3 / Off the Grid, Figure E', "98-99", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U1-L3', "find_area_rotated_square_offgrid", "24 square centimeters", 'Activity 3.3 / Off the Grid, Figure F', "98-99", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U1-L3', "find_area_composite_flag_shape", "72 square inches", 'Activity 3.4 / Maritime Flag, Cool-down', "100-101", figure).
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G6-U1-L3', "This lesson hinges on area invariance under decomposition and rearrangement: students must see that an irregular polygon can be split, rearranged, enclosed, or compared to a larger shape and maintain the same total area. The critical threshold occurs in Activity 3.3 (off-grid figures) and especially with the enclosing-and-subtracting strategy when the inner shape's dimensions are unknown—students cannot numerically compute what they cannot measure, which forces a pivot from grid-counting to reasoning about congruent geometric pieces.").

vision_lesson('IM-G6-U1-L4', 6, 1, 4, "Parallelograms").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U1-L4', teacher, "Compare and contrast (orally) different strategies for determining the area of a parallelogram.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U1-L4', teacher, "Describe (orally and in writing) observations about the opposite side and opposite angles of parallelograms.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U1-L4', teacher, "Explain (orally and in writing) how to find the area of a parallelogram by rearranging its parts or by enclosing it in a rectangle.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U1-L4', student, "Let's investigate the characteristics and area of parallelograms.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G6-U1-L4', "In this lesson, students recall the defining attributes of parallelograms and use reasoning strategies to find areas. One key approach is decomposing a parallelogram and rearranging pieces into a rectangle; another is enclosing the parallelogram in a rectangle and subtracting extra regions. Through working with various parallelograms, students see that shape influences strategy choice. By repeated reasoning, students discover that parallelograms have related rectangles useful for finding area, preparing them to express area as a formula.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U1-L4', building_on, '4.G.A.2').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U1-L4', building_on, '5.G.B').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U1-L4', addressing, '6.G.A.1').
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U1-L4', "parallelogram_area_decompose_rearrange_1", "36 square units", 'Activity 4.2, task 1', "116-117", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U1-L4', "parallelogram_area_enclose_subtract_2", "18 square units", 'Activity 4.2, task 2', "117", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U1-L4', "parallelogram_area_decompose_A", "15 square units", 'Activity 4.3, A', "119", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U1-L4', "parallelogram_area_enclose_B", "12 square units", 'Activity 4.3, B', "119", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U1-L4', "parallelogram_area_decompose_C", "24 square units", 'Activity 4.3, C', "119-120", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U1-L4', "parallelogram_area_practice_2", "45 square units", 'Practice Problem 2', "124", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U1-L4', "parallelogram_area_labeled_dimensions", "30 sq cm", 'Practice Problem 3', "125", text).
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G6-U1-L4', "This lesson's power lies in helping students see that a parallelogram's area always equals the area of a related rectangle—whether found by decomposing and rearranging pieces or by enclosing and subtracting. The most common student confusion: thinking the slant of the sides changes the area, or failing to recognize that orientation doesn't change what a parallelogram is. Students also struggle to choose efficiently between decomposition and enclosure strategies depending on the parallelogram's shape (narrow and stretched favors enclosing; more compact favors rearranging).").

vision_lesson('IM-G6-U1-L5', 6, 1, 5, "Bases and Heights of Parallelograms").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U1-L5', teacher, "Comprehend that the terms \"base\" and \"height\" refer to one side of a parallelogram and the perpendicular distance between that side and the opposite side.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U1-L5', teacher, "Generalize (orally) a process for finding the area of a parallelogram, using the length of a base and the corresponding height.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U1-L5', teacher, "Identify a base and the corresponding height for a parallelogram, and understand that there are two different base-height pairs for any parallelogram.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U1-L5', student, "Let's investigate the area of parallelograms some more.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G6-U1-L5', "In this lesson, students learn about bases and heights of a parallelogram and generalize the process for finding the area of a parallelogram.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U1-L5', addressing, '6.EE.A.2.a').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U1-L5', addressing, '6.EE.A.2.c').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U1-L5', addressing, '6.G.A.1').
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U1-L5', "parallelogram_area_base_height", "Parallelogram A: base 6 (or 4) units, height 4 (or 6) units, area 24 sq units; B: base 5 units, height 3 units, area 15 sq units; C: base 2 units, height 3 units, area 6 sq units; D: base 4 units, height 2 units, area 8 sq units", 'Activity 5.3 main task', "134-135", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U1-L5', "write_expression_for_area_formula", "b · h (or b × h)", 'Activity 5.3, final row of table', "134-135", text).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U1-L5', "parallelogram_area_base_height", "Parallelogram S: base 7, height 6, area 42 sq units; Parallelogram T: base 3, height 6, area 18 sq units", 'Activity 5.4 cool-down', "137", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U1-L5', "parallelogram_area_base_height", "Parallelogram A: 8 sq units; B: 10 sq units; C: 8 sq units", 'Practice Problem 3', "140-141", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U1-L5', "parallelogram_area_base_height", "A: 36 sq cm (base 9 cm, height 4 cm); B: 20 sq cm (base 5 cm, height 4 cm); C: b·h (algebraic)", 'Practice Problem 5', "142", figure).
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G6-U1-L5', "The critical breakthrough is that any side of a parallelogram can serve as a base, and height must be perpendicular to that base—not vertical or along an edge. Students routinely confuse side length with height, think height must lie inside the shape, or assume only a horizontal side can be a base. The key insight, developed through decomposition activities, is that cutting a parallelogram and rearranging it into a rectangle preserves area, yielding the formula b × h.").

vision_lesson('IM-G6-U1-L6', 6, 1, 6, "Area of Parallelograms").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U1-L6', teacher, "Apply the formula for the area of a parallelogram to find the area, the length of the base, or the height, and explain (orally and in writing) the solution method.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U1-L6', teacher, "Choose which measurements to use for calculating the area of a parallelogram when more than one base or height measurement is given, and explain (orally and in writing) the choice.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U1-L6', student, "Let's practice finding the area of parallelograms.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G6-U1-L6', "This lesson allows students to practice using the formula for the area of parallelograms, and to choose the measurements to use as a base and its corresponding height. The parallelograms are shown both on and off a grid. As students work to find the areas, they begin to see that some measurements are more helpful than others. For example, if a parallelogram on a grid has a vertical or horizontal side, and one of those sides is used as a base, then both the base and the height can be relatively easily determined. Students also see that parallelograms with the same base and the same height have the same area because the products of those two numbers are equal, even if the parallelograms look very different.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U1-L6', building_on, '3.OA.A').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U1-L6', addressing, '6.EE.A.2.c').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U1-L6', addressing, '6.G.A.1').
