vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U1-L6', "cooldown_parallelogram_area", "54 square centimeters", 'Activity 6.3, Question 1', "152", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U1-L6', "identify_unused_measurement", "7.5 cm (the slant side)", 'Activity 6.3, Question 2', "152", figure).
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G6-U1-L6', "This lesson is fundamentally about measurement selection: height must be perpendicular distance, never the slant side. Students chronically confuse the side length with the height. The arithmetic (base × height) is elementary, but the geometric reasoning—that two differently-shaped parallelograms with the same base-height products have equal area, and that choosing a horizontal or vertical base on a grid makes perpendicular height visible—is the substantive work.").

vision_lesson('IM-G6-U1-L7', 6, 1, 7, "From Parallelograms to Triangles").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U1-L7', teacher, "Describe (orally and in writing) ways in which two identical triangles can be composed, i.e., into a parallelogram or into a rectangle.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U1-L7', teacher, "Show how any parallelogram can be decomposed into two identical triangles by drawing a diagonal, and generalize (in writing) that this property applies to all parallelograms, but not all quadrilaterals.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U1-L7', student, "I can explain the special relationship between a pair of identical triangles and a parallelogram.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G6-U1-L7', "This lesson prepares students to apply what they know about the area of parallelograms to reason about the area of triangles. Highlighting the relationship between triangles and parallelograms is key. The activities use decomposition (breaking a quadrilateral into triangles) and composition (joining two triangles into a quadrilateral) to help students see that a parallelogram can always be decomposed into two identical triangles, and any two identical triangles can always be composed into a parallelogram.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U1-L7', building_on, '6.G.A.1').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U1-L7', addressing, '6.G.A.1').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U1-L7', building_toward, '6.G.A.1').
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U1-L7', "parallelogram_area_base_height", "2.4 square centimeters", 'Activity 7.1, first task', "163-164", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U1-L7', "rectangle_missing_side_from_area", "1.2 centimeters", 'Activity 7.1, second task', "163-164", figure).
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G6-U1-L7', "This lesson establishes that a triangle occupies exactly half the area of a parallelogram sharing the same base and height. The critical misconception to watch for: students often overgeneralize and think any quadrilateral can be split into two identical triangles by drawing a diagonal. The lesson explicitly shows this is false—only parallelograms work. When checking if triangles match, students may incorrectly conclude congruence by rotation alone; they must physically verify the match-up, potentially rotating or even reflecting the cutout before overlaying.").

vision_lesson('IM-G6-U1-L8', 6, 1, 8, "Area of Triangles").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U1-L8', teacher, "Draw a diagram to show that the area of a triangle is half the area of an associated parallelogram.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U1-L8', teacher, "Explain (orally and in writing) strategies for using the base and height of an associated parallelogram to determine the area of a triangle.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G6-U1-L8', "In this lesson, students reason about areas of triangles by applying strategies such as decomposing and rearranging, or enclosing and subtracting. They observe that the area of a triangle is half of the area of a parallelogram that shares the same base and has the same height. Students arrive at this observation by recalling that two copies of a triangle can be composed into a parallelogram, or by reasoning about rectangles with the same height as the triangle.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U1-L8', addressing, '6.G.A.1').
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U1-L8', "parallelogram_area_composition", "24 square units", 'Activity 8.1 (Warm-up)', "179-180", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U1-L8', "triangle_area_rectangle_method", "8 square units", 'Activity 8.2, Triangle A', "183", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U1-L8', "triangle_area_duplication_method", "10 square units", 'Activity 8.2, Triangle C', "183-184", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U1-L8', "triangle_area_decomposition_method", "12 square units", 'Activity 8.2, Triangle D', "184", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U1-L8', "triangle_area_multiple_strategies", "14 square units", 'Activity 8.4 (Cool-down)', "189-190", figure).
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G6-U1-L8', "This lesson bridges parallelogram area reasoning to triangle area by establishing the half-relationship: a triangle always has half the area of a related parallelogram. The critical misconception is that students rely on counting grid squares rather than composing/decomposing to build the reasoning. A secondary challenge is identifying perpendicular base-height pairs when a triangle's orientation is irregular; students may pick a non-perpendicular side as a base and struggle to locate its height. The lesson works because it leverages what students already know about parallelograms (base times").

vision_lesson('IM-G6-U1-L9', 6, 1, 9, "Formula for the Area of a Triangle").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U1-L9', teacher, "Compare, contrast, and critique (orally) different strategies for determining the area of a triangle.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U1-L9', teacher, "Generalize a process for finding the area of a triangle, and justify (orally and in writing) why this can be abstracted as ½ · b · h.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U1-L9', teacher, "Recognize that any side of a triangle can be considered its base, choose a side to use as the base when calculating the area of a triangle, and identify the corresponding height.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U1-L9', student, "Let's write and use a formula to find the area of a triangle.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G6-U1-L9', "In this lesson, students begin to reason about areas of triangles more methodically: by generalizing their observations up to this point and expressing the area of a triangle in terms of its base and height. Students first learn about bases and heights in a triangle by studying examples and counterexamples. They see that any side of a triangle can be its base, as is the case for parallelograms. They also learn that the height that corresponds to a chosen base is the length of a perpendicular segment that connects the base to the opposite vertex. Next, they identify base-height measurements of triangles and use them to determine area. Then students look for a pattern in their reasoning to help them write a formula for finding the area of any triangle (MP8). They also have a chance to build an informal argument about why the formula works for any triangle (MP3).").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U1-L9', addressing, '6.EE.A.2.a').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U1-L9', addressing, '6.EE.A.2.c').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U1-L9', addressing, '6.G.A.1').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U1-L9', building_toward, '6.G.A.1').
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U1-L9', "write_triangle_area_formula", "b · h ÷ 2 or ½ · b · h or A = ½ · b · h", 'Activity 9.2, Student Task Statement (fi', "202-203", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U1-L9', "calculate_triangle_area_from_labeled_measurements", "15 square cm", 'Activity 9.3, Student Task Statement and', "205-206", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U1-L9', "select_correct_measurements_and_calculate_area", "10.5 square cm", 'Activity 9.3, Student Task Statement and', "205-206", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U1-L9', "apply_formula_with_multiple_valid_base_height_pairs", "9 square inches", 'Activity 9.4, Student Task Statement and', "207-208", figure).
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G6-U1-L9', "Students must understand that the height must be perpendicular to the chosen base (and any side can be a base). The most frequent errors are using non-perpendicular measurements when multiple lengths are labeled, and omitting the division by two from the formula. Connecting to parallelograms (a triangle covers half the area) helps address both misconceptions.").

vision_lesson('IM-G6-U1-L10', 6, 1, 10, "Bases and Heights of Triangles").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U1-L10', teacher, "Draw and label the height that corresponds to a given base of a triangle, making sure it is perpendicular to the base and the correct length.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U1-L10', teacher, "Evaluate (orally) the usefulness of different base-height pairs for finding the area of a given triangle.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U1-L10', student, "Let's use different base-height pairs to find the area of a triangle.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G6-U1-L10', "In this lesson, students further their ability to identify and work with bases and heights in a triangle by drawing a triangle with a given area (reversing the reasoning process they have done so far) and learning to draw (not just to recognize) a segment to show the corresponding height for any given base. The lesson also includes an optional activity in which students learn to choose appropriate base-height pairs to enable area calculations. Because there are three possible pairs of bases and heights in any triangle, some care is needed in identifying the right combination of measurements.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U1-L10', addressing, '6.EE.A.2.c').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U1-L10', addressing, '6.G.A.1').
