vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G6-U1-L10', "Any side of a triangle can serve as a base, and for each base there is exactly one perpendicular height forming the base-height pair. The lesson breaks a core student misconception: that bases must be horizontal and heights must lie inside the triangle. For obtuse triangles, the perpendicular height falls outside the triangle, requiring students to extend the base line and draw the height segment outside the figure's boundary. Students often misuse tools (like index cards) as mere straightedges without ensuring perpendicularity, or confuse side length with height measurement.").

vision_lesson('IM-G6-U1-L11', 6, 1, 11, "Polygons").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U1-L11', teacher, "Compare and contrast (orally) different strategies for finding the area of a polygon.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U1-L11', teacher, "Describe (orally and in writing) the defining characteristics of polygons.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U1-L11', teacher, "Find the area of a polygon, by decomposing it into rectangles and triangles, and present the solution method (using words and other representations).").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U1-L11', student, "Let's investigate polygons and their areas.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G6-U1-L11', "In this lesson, students explore the defining characteristics of polygons. Then they find the areas of polygons by decomposing the regions into triangles or parallelograms.").
