vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U1-L11', building_toward, '6.G.A.1').
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U1-L11', "quadrilateral_area_by_decomposition", "12, 14, 15, 18, 18, or 28 square units (depending on which quadrilateral A-F selected)", 'Activity 11.3 (Quadrilateral Strategies)', "241-242", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U1-L11', "polygon_area_by_decomposition", "40 square units", 'Activity 11.4 (Pinwheel, optional activi', "244-246", figure).
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G6-U1-L11', "This lesson introduces formal polygon vocabulary (vertices, edges, sides) and the decomposition strategy for finding areas. Students often initially conflate the polygon outline with its interior region, focusing on perimeter rather than area. The work stays on unit grids with whole dimensions, so arithmetic is straightforward once the decomposition strategy is grasped; no new calculation demands arise that learner automata cannot handle.").

vision_lesson('IM-G6-U1-L12', 6, 1, 12, "What Is Surface Area?").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U1-L12', teacher, "Calculate the surface area of a rectangular prism and explain (orally and in writing) the solution method.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U1-L12', teacher, "Comprehend that the term 'surface area' (in written and spoken language) refers to how many square units it takes to cover all the faces of a three-dimensional object.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G6-U1-L12', "Student-facing goal: Let's cover the surfaces of some three-dimensional objects.  Lesson Purpose: This lesson introduces students to the concept of surface area. They use what they learned about the area of rectangles to find the surface areas of prisms with rectangular faces. Students begin by exploring surface area in concrete terms, by thinking about the number of square sticky notes it would take to cover a filing cabinet. First, they make an estimate, and then they think about what information is needed to calculate the actual number of sticky notes. Because no techniques are given, students need to make sense of the problem and persevere in solving it (MP1). Students learn that \"surface area\" (in square units) is the number of unit squares it takes to cover all the faces of a three-dimensional figure without gaps or overlaps. Later in the lesson, students determine the surface area of rectangular prisms that are built from snap cubes.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U1-L12', addressing, '6.G.A.4').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U1-L12', building_toward, '6.G.A.4').
