vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G6-U1-L17', "This lesson introduces exponent notation (² and ³) through geometric meaning—squaring and cubing—grounding symbolism in area and volume computation. Students often confuse the exponent (2 or 3) with the side length itself and may multiply by 2 or 3 instead of squaring/cubing; the hands-on building with snap cubes and explicit connection to repeated multiplication help prevent this. Recognizing perfect squares and cubes requires familiarity with multiplication facts; this is the main prerequisite barrier.").

vision_lesson('IM-G6-U1-L18', 6, 1, 18, "Surface Area of a Cube").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U1-L18', teacher, "Generalize a process for finding the surface area of a cube, and justify (orally) why this can be abstracted as 6 · s².").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U1-L18', teacher, "Interpret (orally) expressions that include repeated addition, multiplication, repeated multiplication, or exponents.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U1-L18', teacher, "Write expressions, with or without exponents, to represent the surface area of a given cube.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U1-L18', student, "Let's write a formula to find the surface area of a cube.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G6-U1-L18', "In this lesson, students practice using the exponents \"2\" and \"3\" to express products that describe surface areas and volumes of cubes. They also use exponents to write square units and cubic units. Students begin by writing numerical expressions to represent the surface areas and volumes of cubes with whole-number side lengths. Then, they generalize their observations to write variable expressions for the surface area and volume of any cube. As they write numerical expressions, students practice looking for and making use of structure (MP7). They also practice looking for and expressing regularity in repeated reasoning (MP8) to write formulas for the surface area and the volume of a cube.").
