vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G6-U1-L19', "This lesson bridges pure polygon-area work to the synthesis challenge of three-dimensional surface area: students must identify which faces of a tent actually need material, make assumptions about floor coverage and which ends are included, and correctly decompose composite shapes (especially triangular roof sections requiring slant-height reasoning). The core misconception is incomplete face accounting—students often miss triangular end faces or forget to include the floor. The lesson makes this a feature, not a bug: design decisions about what material to include are explicitly part of the m").

vision_lesson('IM-G6-U2-L1', 6, 2, 1, "Introducing Ratios and Ratio Language").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U2-L1', teacher, "I can write or say a sentence that describes a ratio.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U2-L1', teacher, "I know how to say words and numbers in the correct order to accurately describe the ratio.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U2-L1', student, "Let's describe two quantities at the same time.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G6-U2-L1', "In this lesson, students use collections of objects to make sense of and use ratio language. They see that there are several different ways to describe a situation using ratio language. For example, if we have 12 squares and 6 circles, we can say the ratio of squares to circles is 12 : 6 and the ratio of circles to squares is 6 to 12. We may also see a structure that prompts us to regroup them and say that there are 6 squares for every 2 circles, or 3 squares for every one circle. Expressing associations of quantities in a context—as students will be doing in this lesson—requires students to use ratio language with care. Making groups of physical objects that correspond with \"for every\" language is a concrete way for students to make sense of the problem. It is important that in this first lesson students work with objects that can be physically rearranged. This experience can help students make sense of the increasingly abstract representations that they will encounter as the unit progresses.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U2-L1', building_on, '3.MD.C.6').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U2-L1', addressing, '6.RP.A.1').
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G6-U2-L1', "This lesson focuses on ratio notation, language, and representation. All student tasks involve identifying, writing, or describing ratios from given collections using different symbolic and verbal forms (colon notation such as \"6:3\", \"to\" language such as \"6 to 3\", and \"for every\" language such as \"2 squares for every 1 circle\"). The lesson does not ask students to compute with or operate on numbers via arithmetic. No tasks ask for addition, subtraction, multiplication, or division operations. Practice problems ask students to extract ratio components from given contexts (e.g., \"In a fruit bas").

vision_lesson('IM-G6-U2-L2', 6, 2, 2, "Representing Ratios with Diagrams").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U2-L2', teacher, "Coordinate discrete diagrams and multiple written sentences describing the same ratios.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U2-L2', teacher, "Draw and label discrete diagrams to represent situations involving ratios.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U2-L2', teacher, "Practice reading and writing sentences describing ratios, for example, \"The ratio of these to those is a : b. The ratio of these to those is a to b. For every a of these, there are b of those.\"").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U2-L2', student, "Let's use diagrams to represent ratios.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G6-U2-L2', "In this lesson, students use diagrams to represent situations involving ratios and continue to develop ratio language. Previously, students used words to describe ratios in collections of objects. Here, they also draw diagrams to represent ratios and interpret statements about ratios. Both the visual and verbal descriptions of ratios demand careful attention to language. There is not really a right or wrong way to draw a diagram. What matters is that the diagram accurately represents the quantities, makes sense to the student and others, and can be explained. That said, one goal of this lesson is to help students draw useful diagrams efficiently.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U2-L2', addressing, '6.RP.A.1').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U2-L2', building_toward, '6.RP.A').
