vision_lesson('IM-G6-U2-L13', 6, 2, 13, "Tables and Double Number Line Diagrams").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U2-L13', teacher, "I can create a table that represents a set of equivalent ratios.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U2-L13', teacher, "I can explain why sometimes a table is easier to use than a double number line to solve problems involving equivalent ratios.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U2-L13', teacher, "I include column labels when I create a table, so that the meaning of the numbers is clear.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U2-L13', student, "Let's contrast double number lines and tables.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G6-U2-L13', "In this lesson, students explicitly connect and contrast double number lines and tables. Students consider the ways in which the two representations are alike (for instance, labels are needed and numbers that form equivalent ratios line up) and how they are different. Students examine the relationship between values in different rows in a table. Two features of tables make them more flexible than double number lines. On a double number line, differences between values are represented by lengths. This can support reasoning about relative sizes but can be a limitation for large or small numbers, and a table removes this limitation. On a number line, values are listed in order of size; in a table, pairs of values can be written in any order, allowing more nimble problem solving.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U2-L13', addressing, '6.RP.A.3').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U2-L13', addressing, '6.RP.A.3.a').
