vision_lesson('IM-G6-U3-L1', 6, 3, 1, "Anchoring Units of Measurement").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U3-L1', teacher, "Compare (orally) the relative size of different units of measure for one attribute, that is, length, volume, and weight or mass.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U3-L1', teacher, "Comprehend the approximate size of 1 inch, foot, yard, mile, millimeter, centimeter, meter, kilometer, ounce, pound, ton, gram, kilogram, cup, quart, gallon, milliliter, and liter.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U3-L1', teacher, "Identify which unit is closest to the length, volume, weight, or mass of a given object, and explain (orally) the reasoning.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U3-L1', student, "Let's see how big different things are.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G6-U3-L1', "This lesson activates and builds on students' prior knowledge of units of measurement. It anchors students' perception of standard units of length, volume, weight, and mass with familiar objects serving as benchmarks. This work prepares students to reason about ratios and rates in the context of measurement and to perform unit conversions.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U3-L1', building_on, '2.MD.A.3').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U3-L1', building_on, '4.MD.A.1').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U3-L1', building_on, '5.MD.A.1').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U3-L1', building_toward, '6.RP.A.3.d').
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G6-U3-L1', "This lesson contains no concrete arithmetic computations. It focuses exclusively on measurement unit anchoring through benchmarking, estimation, classification, and reasoning about which units are appropriate for different objects and contexts. All tasks are either estimation activities, unit-classification exercises, or magnitude-comparison reasoning (e.g., identifying whether 500 units refers to feet or yards given a distance context) that require conceptual understanding of relative unit size rather than numerical operations.").

vision_lesson('IM-G6-U3-L2', 6, 3, 2, "Measuring with Different-Size Units").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U3-L2', teacher, "Generalize (orally and in writing) that it takes more of a smaller unit or fewer of a larger unit to measure the same quantity.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U3-L2', teacher, "Given a measurement in one unit, estimate what would be the same amount expressed in a different unit, and explain (orally) the reasoning.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U3-L2', student, "Let's measure things.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G6-U3-L2', "This optional lesson further develops students' understanding of standard units of length, volume, weight, and mass through the tactile experiences of measuring objects. The main idea is that it takes more of a smaller unit and fewer of a larger unit to measure the same quantity. Students begin by comparing two non-standard units of length. They determine whether it would take more regular paper clips or more jumbo paper clips to measure the length of a piece of paper. Then, students engage in similar exercises involving various standard units. In groups, they rotate through up to five measurement stations, using two units to measure one or more quantities at each station. By reasoning repeatedly, students notice regularity—that a measurement in a smaller unit results in a greater value than the same measurement in a larger unit.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U3-L2', building_on, '2.MD.A.2').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U3-L2', addressing, '6.RP.A.3.d').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U3-L2', building_toward, '6.RP.A.3.d').
