vision_lesson('IM-G6-U3-L4', 6, 3, 4, "Comparing Speeds and Prices").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U3-L4', teacher, "Explain (orally and in writing) that if two ratios have the same rate per 1, they are equivalent ratios.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U3-L4', teacher, "Justify (orally and in writing) comparisons of speeds or prices.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U3-L4', teacher, "Recognize that calculating how much for 1 of the same unit is a useful strategy for comparing rates. Express these rates (in spoken and written language) using the word \"per\" and specifying the unit.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U3-L4', student, "Let's compare some speeds and some prices.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G6-U3-L4', "In this lesson, students continue to work with ratios in context and reason about rates per 1. They consider situations and questions about speed and prices. Students see that expressing ratios as rates per 1 is an effective way to compare them. For instance, calculating the distance run in 1 hour or 1 minute shows that runners have the same speed, and calculating the price for 1 item shows which shopping deal is better. Students work toward the understanding that when two ratios have the same rate per 1, they are equivalent ratios, and notice that dividing one quantity in a ratio by the other is an efficient way to find a rate per 1.").
