vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G6-U3-L6', "Every computation this lesson demands maps to an existing automaton, so no task hits a vocabulary boundary. The divisions split into three cleanly-typed families: partitive rate-finding (total shared over N units to get a per-unit rate: $/binder, tomatoes/onion, $/oz, m/s speed, lb/kg) reads as fair_share_equal_groups; quotitive count-finding (total measured in whole rate-sized chunks: notebooks, bracelet-hours, seconds, hours, bananas) reads as measure_groups_of_size; and fractional-rate measurement (applesauce pounds via 1.5, gallons via 100/35) reads as measurement_division. Multiplications").

vision_lesson('IM-G6-U3-L7', 6, 3, 7, "More Rate Comparisons (Grade 6, Unit 3, Lesson 7)").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U3-L7', teacher, "Apply reasoning about ratios and unit rates to compare prices and justify (orally) whether a given price is a good deal.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U3-L7', teacher, "I can choose how to use unit rates to solve problems.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U3-L7', student, "Let's use unit rates like a pro.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G6-U3-L7', "In this lesson, students gain fluency in working with unit rates by solving problems without scaffolding. They choose which unit rate to use to solve a problem, divide to find the desired unit rate, and multiply or divide by the unit rate to answer questions. In the main activity, students decide whether to accept shopping deals by comparing unit rates. In the optional activity, students compare distances given in different units of length to determine which animal ran the farthest, requiring multiple conversion rates in sequence.").
