vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G6-U3-L15', "The lesson's central strategy is to find P% of B by calculating (P/100) · B, which is fundamentally multiplication by a percentage expressed as a decimal or fraction. While the formal vocabulary includes various multiplication strategies (known_product_adjustment, distribute_group_size_split, coordinate_groups_items, etc.), none specifically capture the strategy of \"multiply by a percentage to find a percentage of a quantity.\" Thus, all percentage calculations are coded with kind: NONE, indicating that the lesson's core strategy is not represented in the formal automata vocabulary.").

vision_lesson('IM-G6-U3-L16', 6, 3, 16, "Finding the Percentage").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U3-L16', teacher, "Calculate the percentage one value is of another value and explain (orally) the solution method.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U3-L16', teacher, "Generalize a process for finding the percentage that C is of B and justify (orally) why this can be expressed as C/B · 100.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U3-L16', student, "Let's find percentages in general.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G6-U3-L16', "This lesson is optional because it goes beyond the expectations of grade 6 standards. Students learn to generalize the process for expressing a number as a percentage of another number, or finding what percentage C is of B in a situation where A% of B is C. While students have reasoned about such problems using strategies learned in this unit, developing a general structure that will work with any pair of B and C is not required in this course. Students begin by revisiting fraction and decimal equivalence in the Warm-up. Next, they reason repeatedly about what percentage and what fraction one number is of another number in the context of a situation. They write each fraction in decimal form and then look for regularity in the way the decimals relate to the percentages. Then students generalize the process of expressing one number, C, as a fraction of another, B, as C/B. They see that the decimal equivalent of C/B is related to the numeric value of the percentage by a factor of 100. The percentage C is of B can be found by computing: C/B · 100. The last activity allows students to apply their generalized process to solve similar problems in a new context.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U3-L16', addressing, '6.RP.A.3.c').
