vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G6-U4-L7', "The lesson runs on tape diagrams and measurement-division reasoning rather than a formal invert-and-multiply algorithm; students arrive at fractional quotients (2/3, 3/4, 5/6, 1/10) by partitioning and matching lengths on a diagram. Every demanded computation is measurement division in the fraction family: \"how many groups of size b fit in a,\" or, when a is smaller than b, \"what fraction of a group.\" Each soup and rope comparison also asks students to write a missing-factor multiplication equation (?·b = a) beside the division; that equation represents the same relation, and its unknown is exa").

vision_lesson('IM-G6-U4-L8', 6, 4, 8, "Grade 6, Unit 4, Section C: Algorithm for Fraction Division").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U4-L8', teacher, "Generalize a process for dividing a number n by a fraction a/b as n · b · 1/a, n · b ÷ a, or n · b/a.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U4-L8', teacher, "Use the fraction division algorithm to calculate quotients.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G6-U4-L8', "In this section, students develop a general algorithm for dividing a fraction by a fraction, pulling together the thread of reasoning from earlier lessons. First, students use tape diagrams to reason repeatedly about division of a whole number by a unit fraction, looking for structure and regularity. They then extend this reasoning to division by a non-unit fraction, generalizing that to divide a number n by a non-unit fraction a/b is to find how many unit fractions 1/b are in n (find n ÷ 1/b) and then how many groups of a unit fractions can be formed (find n ÷ 1/b ÷ a). For example, to divide 6 by 3/4 is to find how many 1/4 are in 6 (6 ÷ 1/4) and then how many groups of three 1/4 can be formed (6 ÷ 1/4 ÷ 3). Students then extend these generalized steps to divide a fraction by a fraction, concluding that to find n ÷ a/b is to find n · b · 1/a or n · b/a, and finally practice applying this algorithm to calculate quotients.").
