vision_lesson('IM-G6-U4-L14', 6, 4, 14, "Fractional Lengths in Triangles and Prisms").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U4-L14', teacher, "Calculate the base or the height of a triangle given its area and the other measurement.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U4-L14', teacher, "Determine the volume of a rectangular prism by counting how many 1/2-inch or 1/3-inch cubes it takes to build, and explain (orally and in writing) the solution method.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U4-L14', teacher, "Generalize that the volume of a rectangular prism with fractional edge lengths can be found by multiplying the edge lengths.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U4-L14', student, "Let's explore area and volume when fractions are involved.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G6-U4-L14', "This lesson transitions students from thinking about the area of two-dimensional figures with fractional linear measurements to reasoning about the volume of prisms with fractional edge lengths. Students begin by solving problems about triangles, finding area given base and height, and calculating an unknown base or height given the area and the other measurement. Next, students explore the volume of rectangular prisms with non-whole-number edge lengths. They find volume by packing prisms with unit-fraction cubes, quantifying the number of cubes, multiplying by the volume of one cube, and eventually multiplying the edge lengths directly (MP8).").
