vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G6-U6-L8', "This lesson asks students to distinguish between expressions that are equal at one or more specific values (e.g., x + 2 and 3x both equal 3 when x = 1) and expressions that are equivalent (equal for all values of the variable, e.g., x + 3 and 3 + x). Students often confuse these categories—they may think that because two expressions match for one test value, they must be equivalent. The core insight is that equivalence requires testing the full logical structure (using properties of operations) rather than spot-checking one value.").

