vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G6-U6-L18', "This lesson distinguishes relationships by type: constant-area and constant-volume situations produce inverse (hyperbolic) relationships where one variable decreases as the other increases, while exponential growth produces rapid, curved growth. Students often misread graphs—confusing which variable is independent—and struggle to interpret points in context (e.g., what does the point (2, 18) mean for a rectangle with area 36?). The lesson demands coordinating three representations simultaneously, which can overwhelm students who haven't internalized what makes each representation useful.").

vision_lesson('IM-G6-U6-L19', 6, 6, 19, "Tables, Equations, and Graphs, Oh My!").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U6-L19', teacher, "Create a verbal description and a graph to represent the relationship shown in an equation and table.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U6-L19', teacher, "Identify tables and equations that represent the same relationship and justify (orally) the match.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U6-L19', teacher, "Interpret and critique (orally) different representations of the same relationship: table, equation, graph, and verbal description.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U6-L19', student, "Let's explore some equations from real-world situations.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G6-U6-L19', "In this culminating lesson, students look at several examples of equations that represent important relationships from real-world situations. In the first activity, students briefly examine eight relationships, matching an equation and a table that represent the same relationship. In the following activities, each student works more closely with one of the relationships: interpreting the equation, continuing the table, and creating a graph. This gives students an opportunity to become an expert on one of these relationships and then use multiple representations to explain their understanding to others.").
