vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G6-U7-L1', "Correcting the first pass: it claimed signed arithmetic has \"no automaton in the vocabulary,\" which is false. The vocabulary carries an integer category (signed_number_location_and_order, signed_addition_with_sign_relation, inequality_solution_set_representation). This lesson's on-target demand is number-line location, not signed computation: the activity narrative states outright \"This task is not about operations with signed numbers, but rather why we extend our number system beyond positive numbers,\" and goal 3 / standard 6.NS.C.6 is \"the number line can be extended to represent negative nu").

vision_lesson('IM-G6-U7-L2', 6, 7, 2, "Points on the Number Line").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U7-L2', teacher, "Comprehend that two numbers are called \"opposites\" when they are the same distance from zero, but on different sides of the number line.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U7-L2', teacher, "Interpret a point on the number line that represents a positive or negative rational number.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U7-L2', teacher, "Plot a point on a number line to represent a positive or negative rational number.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U7-L2', student, "Let's plot positive and negative numbers on the number line.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G6-U7-L2', "In this lesson, students examine and make use of the structure of the number line (MP7). Students begin by considering which values could be represented by a point on a horizontal number line by reasoning about position in relation to other known values on the number line. Then they revisit the context of temperature, represented by a vertical number line, extending previous work interpreting equally spaced divisions to the negative part of the number line. Next, students create folded number lines out of tracing paper to reinforce the symmetry of the number line and to reason about opposites—numbers that are the same distance from zero but on opposite sides of the number line. Lastly, students are introduced to the term rational number as a number that can be expressed as a positive or negative fraction or zero. Students will have more practice placing rational numbers on the number line in future lessons. The focus in this lesson is the concept of opposites rather than plotting different kinds of rational numbers.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U7-L2', building_on, '3.NF.A').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U7-L2', building_on, '4.NF.C').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U7-L2', addressing, '6.NS.C.6').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U7-L2', addressing, '6.NS.C.6.a').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U7-L2', addressing, '6.NS.C.6.c').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U7-L2', building_toward, '6.NS.C.6.a').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U7-L2', building_toward, '6.NS.C.6.c').
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G6-U7-L2', "This lesson contains no concrete arithmetic computation tasks. The lesson's activities focus entirely on conceptual understanding: reading values from number-line and thermometer diagrams, identifying/naming opposites, understanding the structure of the number line and its symmetry, and introducing the concept of rational numbers as representations. The lesson includes representation tasks (e.g., representing temperatures with positive/negative numbers) and identification tasks (e.g., naming the opposite of -5), but no tasks requiring arithmetic operations with concrete operands. The practice").

vision_lesson('IM-G6-U7-L3', 6, 7, 3, "Grade 6 Unit 7 Practice Problems (Problem 7, from Unit 3 Lesson 3)").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U7-L3', student, "Determine whether a weight that doubles in pounds also doubles in kilograms, and explain your reasoning.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G6-U7-L3', "Not visible in this PDF excerpt (practice problems section only)").
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G6-U7-L3', "This PDF excerpt shows only a practice problem (page 83), not a full lesson guide. The problem is conceptual: it asks whether a proportional relationship (doubling) holds across unit systems without providing a concrete starting weight value to compute. The reasoning involves algebraic expressions (x pounds → 2x pounds; x ÷ 2.2 kilograms → 2(x ÷ 2.2) kilograms) but no specific operands. No task_events with concrete arithmetic are present. Standards, lesson purpose, teacher goals, and the formal \"Let's...\" student goal are not visible in this page excerpt. If IM-G6-U7-L3 is a multi-page lesson,").

vision_lesson('IM-G6-U7-L4', 6, 7, 4, "Ordering Rational Numbers").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U7-L4', teacher, "Compare rational numbers without a context, and express (orally and in writing) the comparisons using the phrases \"greater than,\" \"less than,\" and \"opposite.\"").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U7-L4', teacher, "Comprehend that all negative numbers are less than all positive numbers.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U7-L4', teacher, "Order rational numbers from least to greatest, and explain (orally and through other representations) the reasoning.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U7-L4', student, "Let's order rational numbers.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G6-U7-L4', "In this lesson, students practice ordering rational numbers and using precise language to describe the relationships between numbers plotted on a number line (MP6). Students begin by using the symbol <, >, or = to compare pairs of numbers. Next, they work with a partner to put sets of cards in order from least to greatest. The cards include both positive and negative rational numbers. Students then compare the locations of points on a horizontal number line using phrases, such as \\\"greater than,\\\" \\\"less than,\\\" \\\"opposite,\\\" and \\\"negative.\\\"").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U7-L4', building_on, '4.NBT.A.2').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U7-L4', building_on, '5.NBT.A.3.b').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U7-L4', building_on, '6.NS.C.6.a').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U7-L4', addressing, '6.NS.C').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U7-L4', addressing, '6.NS.C.6').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U7-L4', addressing, '6.NS.C.6.a').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U7-L4', addressing, '6.NS.C.7').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U7-L4', building_toward, '6.NS.C.7').
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G6-U7-L4', "This lesson contains no concrete arithmetic computation tasks. All student activities focus on ordering rational numbers from least to greatest, using inequality symbols (<, >, =) to compare pre-given numbers, and employing precise mathematical language (greater than, less than, opposite, negative) to describe relationships on number lines. There are no tasks requiring the student to compute sums, differences, products, or quotients. The lesson is a language-and-representation-focused activity that precedes or accompanies computational work in other lessons.").

vision_lesson('IM-G6-U7-L5', 6, 7, 5, "Using Negative Numbers to Make Sense of Contexts").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U7-L5', teacher, "I can explain and use negative numbers in situations involving money.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U7-L5', teacher, "I can interpret and use negative numbers in different contexts.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U7-L5', teacher, "Interpret a table of signed numbers that represent how a quantity changed.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U7-L5', teacher, "Recognize that signed numbers can be useful to represent changes in a quantity in opposite directions, e.g., money received and money paid, inventory bought and inventory sold, etc.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U7-L5', student, "Let's make sense of negative amounts of money.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G6-U7-L5', "In this lesson, students are introduced to conventions for using signed numbers to represent money spent and received, as well as inventory gained and lost. Students examine a table detailing the inventory and value in dollars of items sold at a hardware store. They make sense of what positive and negative numbers mean in relation to the inventory (items purchased or sold) and also in relation to the items' value in dollars (MP2). An optional activity about the inventory in a vending machine offers additional practice interpreting signed numbers in context. Since students do not operate on signed numbers in this grade, this lesson is simply an introduction to the convention of using signed numbers to represent a change in money or a change in inventory. Students will study addition and subtraction of signed numbers in a future course.").
