vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U7-L7', addressing, '6.NS.C.7.d').
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G6-U7-L7', "This lesson contains no explicit arithmetic computation tasks. All student activities involve comparison, ordering, and interpretation of rational numbers and absolute values: positioning points on number lines based on contextual constraints, requesting and sharing information via the Information Gap routine, writing comparison statements in words and mathematical symbols, and evaluating the truth of inequality statements. The lesson assumes prior mastery of absolute-value evaluation and focuses on applying that knowledge to compare and order rational numbers with and without absolute values").

vision_lesson('IM-G6-U7-L8', 6, 7, 8, "Writing and Graphing Inequalities").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U7-L8', teacher, "Coordinate verbal, algebraic, and number line representations of inequalities.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U7-L8', teacher, "Critique (orally and in writing) possible values given for a situation with a constraint, including determining whether the boundary value is included and making sense of situations with discrete quantities.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U7-L8', teacher, "Interpret phrases that describe a quantity constrained by a maximum or minimum acceptable value, e.g., \"at least,\" \"at most,\" \"up to,\" \"more than,\" \"less than,\" and write an inequality statement to represent the constraint.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U7-L8', student, "Let's write inequalities.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G6-U7-L8', "In this lesson, students extend their work with inequality statements by considering comparisons with an unknown quantity. Students begin by examining an image of a person standing next to a basketball hoop and determine possible minimum and maximum heights of the hoop. They express possible heights as a variable in an inequality statement. Next, students are presented with two types of scenarios and must reason about the quantities involved (MP2). In one type, the variable represents a measurement, and the possible values can usually be any number within the range satisfied by the constraint. In the second type, where the variable represents a count of people or objects, the possible values are restricted to whole numbers within the range. Students also consider whether the constraint itself is included or excluded in the set of possible values, and they learn how to indicate this result on the number line representation with open or closed circles. Note that inequality symbols in grade 6 are limited to &lt; and &gt;. For situations where the constraint itself is included, students write 2 statements, such as x &gt; 5 and x = 5.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U7-L8', addressing, '6.EE.B.6').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U7-L8', addressing, '6.EE.B.8').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U7-L8', addressing, '6.NS.C.7.b').
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G6-U7-L8', "This lesson focuses on representing and interpreting inequality constraints through verbal, algebraic, and graphical modalities. Students estimate bounds on a measurement, write inequality statements using < and > symbols, evaluate whether specific values satisfy inequality constraints (e.g., checking 487 > 500), and graph solution sets on number lines using open/closed circles to mark boundary inclusion. No arithmetic operations (addition, subtraction, multiplication, division) are performed; the demand is representational and comparative, not computational. The real mathematical work lies in").

