vision_lesson('IM-G6-U7-L10', 6, 7, 10, "Interpreting Inequalities").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U7-L10', teacher, "Critique (orally and in writing) possible values given for a situation with more than one constraint, including whether fractional or negative values are reasonable.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U7-L10', teacher, "Interpret (orally and in writing) unbalanced hanger diagrams, and write inequality statements to represent relationships between the weights on an unbalanced hanger diagram.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U7-L10', teacher, "Write and interpret inequality statements that include more than one variable.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U7-L10', student, "Let's examine what inequalities can tell us.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G6-U7-L10', "In this lesson, students explore situations where some of the solutions to inequalities do not make sense in the context of the situation. They reason carefully about a situation's constraints when determining reasonable solutions (MP2). Students begin by addressing a common mistake made when the variable is written on the right side of an inequality, such as 15 < n, thinking that n must be less than 15. Next, students consider the context of points scored in a basketball game. While many numbers can be solutions to an inequality describing the number of points scored by a player, only some of those solutions make sense in context. Lastly, students look at inequalities by using the familiar context of hanger diagrams, contrasting the balanced hangers of equations with the unbalanced hangers of inequalities.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U7-L10', addressing, '6.EE.A.2.b').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U7-L10', addressing, '6.EE.B.5').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U7-L10', addressing, '6.EE.B.6').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U7-L10', addressing, '6.EE.B.8').
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G6-U7-L10', "This lesson focuses on interpreting inequalities and reasoning about their solutions in context. It does not present concrete arithmetic computation problems. Instead, students engage in algebraic reasoning about inequality notation, relationships between quantities in hanger diagrams, and contextual constraints on variables. The mathematical demand is on understanding inequality symbols, comparing quantities, and logic—not on arithmetic operations (addition, subtraction, multiplication, division). No automata in the controlled vocabulary apply because the lesson makes no demand for concrete a").

vision_lesson('IM-G6-U7-L11', 6, 7, 11, "Points in the Coordinate Plane").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U7-L11', teacher, "Generalize the signs of coordinates that represent locations in each quadrant of the coordinate plane.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U7-L11', teacher, "Plot a point given its coordinates, or identify the coordinates of a given point in the coordinate plane.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U7-L11', teacher, "Recognize that in the coordinate plane, the horizontal and vertical axes include negative numbers.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U7-L11', student, "Let's explore the coordinate plane.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G6-U7-L11', "In this lesson, students make use of structure when they extend the vertical and horizontal axes to include positive and negative numbers and create the coordinate plane (MP7). The crossing axes create quadrants, the four regions of the coordinate plane. Students begin the lesson by revisiting ordered pairs in order to describe the location of three points in the coordinate plane. They continue to practice identifying the coordinates of points as well as which quadrant a point is located in. Students gain additional experience by choosing, plotting, and writing the coordinates of points in order to hit targets drawn in the coordinate plane.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U7-L11', building_on, '5.G.A.1').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U7-L11', addressing, '6.NS.C.6.b').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U7-L11', addressing, '6.NS.C.6.c').
