vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G6-U7-L13', "This lesson centers on interpreting coordinate points in context (money and temperature); its own activities demand only subtraction, which the vocabulary covers via compare_by_matching_difference. Correction: the first-pass largest-difference event carried fabricated operands subtract(20,10) — no day on the page-194 graph shows a high of 20 with a low of 10. It is corrected to day 3's figure-read values subtract(21,11)=10, which the answer key confirms as one of days 3, 6, and 7 all yielding a 10-degree-Fahrenheit difference (day 6: 17-7; day 7: 7-(-3)). The cool-down comparison 1.2-(-3.5)=4.").

vision_lesson('IM-G6-U7-L14', 6, 7, 14, "Distances in the Coordinate Plane").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U7-L14', teacher, "Compare and contrast (orally and in writing) the coordinates for points in different locations on the coordinate plane.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U7-L14', teacher, "Determine the vertical or horizontal distance between two points on the coordinate plane that share the same x- or y-coordinate.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U7-L14', teacher, "Generalize (orally) about the coordinates of points that are reflected across the x- or y-axis.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U7-L14', student, "Let's explore distance on the coordinate plane.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G6-U7-L14', "In this lesson, students explore the relationship between points with opposite coordinates and develop strategies for finding vertical and horizontal distances in the coordinate plane. Students begin by plotting points in one of the four quadrants. By comparing the coordinates of points in the different quadrants, students generalize patterns about their signs (MP8). Next, students explore points where the x- or y-coordinates are opposites and see that they are also reflections across the x- or y-axis. Then students develop strategies for finding the distance between two points where the coordinates may not be integers.").
