vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G6-U7-L14', "The lesson restricts distance to horizontal and vertical (axis-aligned) cases; general two-dimensional or diagonal distance is out of scope by design, so the cool-down's non-aligned pairs (answered \"about 9.5\" and \"about 6.5\" units) and the \"Are You Ready for More?\" circle question have no automaton in this vocabulary and are not extracted. The dedicated automaton axis_aligned_coordinate_distance (knowledge/strategies/math/geometry_action_pairs.pl:758) carries an integer-coordinate guard and returns abs(DirectedDifference). It accepts the integer-coordinate practice tasks 2a-2c and computes each length").

vision_lesson('IM-G6-U7-L15', 6, 7, 15, "Shapes in the Coordinate Plane").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U7-L15', teacher, "Determine the total length of multiple horizontal and vertical segments in the coordinate plane that are connected end to end.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U7-L15', teacher, "Draw a polygon in the coordinate plane given the coordinates for its vertices.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U7-L15', teacher, "Explain (orally) that coordinates can be a useful way of describing geometric figures or modeling real-world locations.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U7-L15', student, "Let's use the coordinate plane to solve problems and puzzles.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G6-U7-L15', "In this lesson, students apply their understanding of rational coordinates and distance in the coordinate plane to construct polygons and navigate a maze. Students begin by constructing a polygon in the coordinate plane to meet given requirements. Next students plot coordinates in all four quadrants and connect points to create polygons. Lastly, students analyze the structure of a maze drawn in a coordinate plane to determine coordinates and distances (MP7).").
