vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U7-L16', "gcd(90, 75)", "15", 'practice_3', "235", text).
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G6-U7-L16', "The lesson's core demand—finding the greatest common factor (GCF) of two numbers—does not map to any automaton in the available vocabulary. GCF is a number theory operation distinct from arithmetic (addition, subtraction, multiplication, division) or division strategies. Students find GCF by enumerating factors through divisibility reasoning, then identifying the largest shared factor. This operation exceeds the scope of standard computational automata in the model.\"").

vision_lesson('IM-G6-U7-L17', 6, 7, 17, "Common Multiples").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U7-L17', teacher, "Comprehend (orally and in writing) the terms \"multiple,\" \"common multiple,\" and \"least common multiple.\"").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U7-L17', teacher, "Explain (orally and in writing) how to calculate the least common multiple of two whole numbers.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U7-L17', teacher, "List the multiples of a number, and identify common multiples for two numbers in a real-world situation.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U7-L17', student, "Let's use multiples to solve problems.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G6-U7-L17', "In this lesson, students are introduced to common multiples of two numbers as products that result from multiplying each of the two numbers by some whole number. They are also introduced to the least common multiples of two whole numbers as the smallest multiple shared by both numbers. Students reason abstractly when they use common multiples to solve problems in contextual situations (MP2).").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U7-L17', addressing, '6.NS.B.4').
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G6-U7-L17', "This lesson's mathematical work (identifying multiples, finding common multiples, determining LCM) is conceptual and enumerative rather than computational. Students compare lists of multiples, recognize patterns, and discover the LCM concept. While students may implicitly compute (e.g., multiply to verify that 2 bunches of roses equals 24 flowers), no task explicitly asks for basic arithmetic computation on concrete operands with a named strategy (e.g., \"compute 3 × 8\"). The lesson's content domain—multiple enumeration and LCM discovery—does not align with the controlled vocabulary of computat").

vision_lesson('IM-G6-U7-L18', 6, 7, 18, "Using Common Multiples and Common Factors").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U7-L18', teacher, "Choose to calculate the greatest common factor or least common multiple to solve a problem about a real-world situation, and justify (orally) the choice.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U7-L18', teacher, "Present (orally, in writing, and using other representations) the solution method for a problem involving greatest common factor or least common multiple.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U7-L18', student, "Let's use common factors and common multiples to solve problems.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G6-U7-L18', "In this lesson, students apply what they have learned about factors and multiples to solve a variety of problems. Students make sense of problems by determining whether they involve finding factors or multiples before working with a partner to solve them (MP1).").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U7-L18', addressing, '6.NS.B.4').
