vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G6-U7-L18', "The first-pass extraction fabricated both of its task_events: multiply(12,8) and multiply(4,24) were cited on pages 261 and 262, which do not exist in this document (the lesson runs 249-258), and their excerpts (\"Find the product of 12 and 8\", \"Find the product of the greatest common factor and the least common multiple of 12 and 8\") appear nowhere in the lesson. Both were deleted as unconfirmable. The lesson contains no direct whole-number product task; its work is finding greatest common factors and least common multiples in context. Those operations map to the multiplication-family automata").

vision_lesson('IM-G6-U7-L19', 6, 7, 19, "Drawing in the Coordinate Plane").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U7-L19', teacher, "Generate a list of ordered pairs to create an image in the coordinate plane, and explain (orally) the reasoning.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U7-L19', student, "Let's draw on the coordinate plane.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G6-U7-L19', "In this optional culminating lesson, students use graphing technology to plot ordered pairs and create images. Using graphing technology for this lesson is highly recommended over doing it with pencil and paper. In the first activity, students recreate a given image to help familiarize them with how the graphing technology works. The second activity, where students design their own image, could be lengthened or shortened as needed by instructing students to create an image with more or less detail. Using graphing technology gives students an opportunity to attend to precision (MP6) because the program graphs exactly what they enter and will not guess at what they might have meant if they input a point incorrectly.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U7-L19', addressing, '6.G.A.3').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U7-L19', addressing, '6.NS.C.8').
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G6-U7-L19', "This is a culminating coordinate-geometry lesson with no arithmetic computation tasks. Both activities (recreating a cat image from coordinates and designing an original image) require students to identify, list, or enter ordered pairs and plot them on a coordinate plane using graphing technology. The work is entirely representational/geometric—reading points off a graph or visualizing an image as a set of coordinates—rather than computational. The extension adds graphing inequalities (6.NS.C.8). The single applicable strategy from the geometry vocabulary is ordered_pair_coordinate_plot, but t").

vision_lesson('IM-G6-U8-L1', 6, 8, 1, "Got Data?").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U8-L1', teacher, "Ask survey questions (orally) and record responses (in writing); include units of measurement when reporting numerical data (orally and in writing).").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U8-L1', teacher, "Comprehend and use the terms 'numerical' and 'categorical' to describe data sets (orally and in writing).").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U8-L1', teacher, "Interpret various representations of data sets and determine whether it is reasonable that a verbal description represents a given numerical data set.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U8-L1', student, "Let's explore different kinds of data.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G6-U8-L1', "Students begin the unit by collecting data about themselves by measuring and answering survey questions, studying the different types of responses collected, and identifying the appropriate variables and units being measured. Students learn about categorical and numerical data then determine whether a particular survey question will produce one type of data or the other. They also use dot plots (similar to line plots in earlier grades) as a way to represent data and make sense of what data points mean in context.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U8-L1', building_on, '2.MD.D.9').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U8-L1', building_on, '4.MD.A.1').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U8-L1', building_on, '5.MD.B').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U8-L1', addressing, '6.SP.B').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U8-L1', building_toward, '6.SP.B.4').
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G6-U8-L1', "This lesson is a data-literacy entry point where the core intellectual work is conceptual rather than computational. Students must distinguish between numerical data (quantities subject to measurement and comparison) and categorical data (qualities sorted into categories), and hold this distinction constant across contexts. The pervasive misconception is that any number string is numerical data; students confuse zip codes, area codes, and month numbers with quantities. A secondary challenge: recognizing that the same data can be represented multiple ways (e.g., months as names versus as numera").

vision_lesson('IM-G6-U8-L2', 6, 8, 2, "Statistical Questions").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U8-L2', teacher, "Justify (orally) whether a question is \"statistical\" based on whether variability is expected in the data that could be collected.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U8-L2', teacher, "Match survey questions to data sets representing possible responses and justify (in writing) why they match.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U8-L2', student, "Let's look more closely at data and the questions they can help us answer.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G6-U8-L2', "In this lesson, students continue to analyze questions and the kinds of responses they can expect from those questions. They begin to recognize variability in data and learn about statistical questions and how they differ from non-statistical questions. In order to define variability, students categorize data sets and name the categories to make use of structure by seeking mathematically important similarities between the objects (MP7).").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U8-L2', building_on, '5.MD.B.2').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U8-L2', addressing, '6.SP.A').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U8-L2', addressing, '6.SP.A.1').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U8-L2', addressing, '6.SP.B').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U8-L2', addressing, '6.SP.B.5.b').
