vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G6-U8-L7', "This lesson shifts from arithmetic computation to visual pattern-reading and statistical reasoning. Histograms group measurement data into equal-width intervals to reveal distributions; students must count frequencies accurately, choose reasonable bin widths, and interpret shapes to estimate center and spread. Common pitfalls: confusing histograms with bar graphs (no gaps between bars), losing count while binning raw data, and treating the modal bin as an exact value. The deeper challenge is accepting that histograms trade individual precision for aggregate insight—you can describe the shape a").

vision_lesson('IM-G6-U8-L8', 6, 8, 8, "Describing Distributions on Histograms").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U8-L8', teacher, "Compare and contrast (orally) bar graphs and histograms, recognizing that descriptions of shape, center, and spread don't pertain to bar graphs.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U8-L8', teacher, "Describe (orally and in writing) the overall shape and features of a distribution represented on a histogram, including peaks, clusters, gaps, and symmetry.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U8-L8', teacher, "Identify histograms that display distributions with specific features.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U8-L8', student, "Let's describe distributions displayed in histograms.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G6-U8-L8', "In this lesson, students explore various shapes and features of a distribution displayed in a histogram. They use the structure (MP7) to look for symmetry, peaks, clusters, gaps, and any unusual values in histograms. Students also begin to consider how features such as symmetry might affect how we characterize a data set. This work is informal, but helps to prepare students to better understand measures of center and spread later in the unit. In this lesson, students also distinguish between the uses and construction of bar graphs and histograms.").
