vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U8-L13', student, "Here is a list of statistical questions. What data would you collect and analyze to answer each question? For numerical data, include the unit of measurement that you would use.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G6-U8-L13', "Not visible in this practice-problems page. The lesson introduction would contain the Lesson Purpose paragraph.").
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G6-U8-L13', "This lesson asks students to distinguish statistical questions (those expecting variability across responses) from non-statistical questions, and to plan feasible data-collection methods with appropriate units. The primary challenge is recognizing that typical or general answers demand collecting multiple data points—not finding a single answer. Students often propose vague collection methods without specifying sample boundaries or measurement units; the lesson expects precision in both scope and units.").

vision_lesson('IM-G6-U8-L14', 6, 8, 14, "Comparing Mean and Median").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U8-L14', teacher, "Choose which measure of center to use to describe a given data set and justify (orally and in writing) the choice.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U8-L14', teacher, "Explain (orally) that the median is a better estimate of a typical value than the mean for distributions that are not symmetric or contain values far from the center.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U8-L14', teacher, "Generalize how the shape of the distribution affects the mean and median of a data set.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U8-L14', student, "Let's compare the mean and median of data sets.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G6-U8-L14', "In this lesson, students investigate whether the mean or the median is a more appropriate measure of the center of a distribution in a given context. They learn that when the distribution is symmetric, the mean and median have similar values, so the mean should usually be used for its connection to fairness. When the distribution is not symmetric, however, the mean is often greatly influenced by values that are far from the majority of the data points. In this case, the median may be a better choice.").
