vision_lesson('IM-G6-U8-L16', 6, 8, 16, "Box Plots").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U8-L16', teacher, "Compare and contrast (orally) a dot plot and a box plot that represent the same data set.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U8-L16', teacher, "Create a box plot to represent a data set.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U8-L16', teacher, "Describe (orally) the parts of a box plot that correspond with each number in the five-number summary, the range, and the IQR of a data set.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U8-L16', student, "Let's explore how box plots can help us summarize distributions.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G6-U8-L16', "Students use the five-number summary to construct box plots. They begin with a kinesthetic activity identifying the median, quartiles, and range from class data on name lengths, positioning themselves on a number line and using tape to mark a human box plot. Then they draw box plots on paper, discovering that unlike dot plots, box plots cannot reveal individual data points but instead summarize distributions by showing range, middle half location, and quarter divisions. The lesson emphasizes that box plots are useful for comparing distributions and seeing shape, center, and spread at a glance.").
