vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U8-L16', "create_box_plot_from_raw_data", "Ordered data: 3 4 5 5 5 7 9 10 11 11 12 12; minimum: 3, Q1: 5, Q2: 9.5, Q3: 11.5, maximum: 12", 'Practice Problems, Problem 3', "285-286", text).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U8-L16', "box_plot_count_in_rectangle", "50 mice (half the total of 100)", 'Practice Problems, Problem 4', "286", figure).
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G6-U8-L16', "Box plots summarize a distribution by displaying only the five-number summary, not individual data points—the key tradeoff students must grasp. Students most commonly struggle with three ideas: (1) conflating box plots with dot plots, or not understanding why a box plot cannot show individual values; (2) misidentifying the box width as the full range rather than the IQR (interquartile range), which represents only the middle 50% of data; (3) incorrectly calculating quartiles when the number of data values is odd versus even, especially the median's role in splitting the upper and lower halves.").

vision_lesson('IM-G6-U8-L17', 6, 8, 17, "Using Box Plots").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U8-L17', teacher, "Compare and contrast (orally and in writing) box plots that represent different data sets, including ones with the same median but very different IQRs and vice versa.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U8-L17', teacher, "Determine what information is needed to solve problems about comparing box plots. Ask questions to elicit that information.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U8-L17', teacher, "Interpret a box plot to answer (orally) statistical questions about a data set.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G6-U8-L17', "In this lesson, students use box plots to make sense of data in context (MP2), compare distributions, and answer statistical questions about a situation. Students compare box plots for distributions that have the same median but different IQRs, as well as box plots with the same IQRs but different medians. They recognize and articulate that the centers are the same but the spreads are different in the first case, and that the centers are different but the spreads are the same in the second case. They use this understanding to compare typical members of different groups in terms of the context of the problem (MP2).").
