vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G6-U9-L2', "This lesson develops rate reasoning and part-whole ratio work in real-world (water and energy) contexts. Students choose among multiple representations (tables, double number lines, tape diagrams) to organize their reasoning. The core challenge is not the arithmetic itself—once students identify whether they need a unit rate (divide) or to scale a known rate (multiply)—but translating a word problem's structure into the correct operation and keeping track of what quantities mean.").

vision_lesson('IM-G6-U9-L3', 6, 9, 3, "Making Paper").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U9-L3', teacher, "Choose and create diagrams to help solve problems that involve ratios and a total amount.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U9-L3', teacher, "Explain a method to solve ratio problems involving large numbers.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U9-L3', student, "Let's decide what material to make paper from.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G6-U9-L3', "In this optional lesson, students compare the energy used to make paper from two different sources: tree fiber or recycled material. This lesson begins with a Warm-up meant to familiarize students with vocabulary related to energy consumption and carbon dioxide emission. This promotes students' making sense of the problem and their perseverance in solving it (MP1). They then analyze the current consumption and emission of two paper mills and construct arguments regarding whether or not one of the paper mills should change the material used to create paper (MP3).").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U9-L3', addressing, '6.RP.A.3').
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U9-L3', "paper_production_from_total_energy", "1,500 pounds per mill; 3,000 pounds total", 'Activity 3.2, question 1', "25-26", text).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U9-L3', "total_co2_emission_from_paper_production", "19,500 pounds of carbon dioxide", 'Activity 3.2, question 2', "25-26", text).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U9-L3', "energy_change_from_material_conversion", "3,000 kWh less energy", 'Activity 3.2, question 3a', "25-26", text).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U9-L3', "co2_emission_change_from_material_conversion", "7,500 pounds decrease in emission", 'Activity 3.2, question 3b', "25-26", text).
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G6-U9-L3', "This lesson hinges on part-part-whole ratio structure: two mills in a 4:2 energy-consumption ratio that produce equal paper amounts. Students commonly err by dividing the total energy by individual rates without recognizing the 2:1 ratio structure, or by treating each mill separately. Scaling with large numbers (9,000 kWh) demands strategic representation (tables, double number lines, tape diagrams); direct computation obscures the mathematical structure students need to see.").

vision_lesson('IM-G6-U9-L4', 6, 9, 4, "If Our Class Were the World").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U9-L4', teacher, "Generate (orally and in writing) mathematical questions about the world's population, e.g., \"How many people . . . ?\"").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U9-L4', teacher, "Interpret and approximate characteristics of the world's population using percentages and equivalent ratios.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U9-L4', teacher, "Present (using words and other representations) a comparison that uses the number of students in the class to represent the proportion of the world's population with a particular characteristic.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U9-L4', student, "Let's use math to better understand our world.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G6-U9-L4', "This lesson is optional. In this lesson, students explore what their class would be like if its ratios were equivalent to that of the world population. In the process, students reason abstractly and quantitatively with percentages that are not whole numbers, using knowledge gained in a previous unit (MP2). Moreover, the ratios will be \"close\" to being equivalent because the exact world population is not known, and all populations need to be whole numbers, which requires students to attend to precision (MP6).").
