vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G6-U9-L4', "This lesson asks students to scale world population percentages to a classroom using proportional reasoning. The core challenge is recognizing that percentages yield approximations requiring whole-number rounding for people; a scaled class can never perfectly represent world proportions, only approximately.").

vision_lesson('IM-G6-U9-L5', 6, 9, 5, "How Do We Choose?").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U9-L5', teacher, "Comprehend the terms \"majority\" and \"supermajority\" (in spoken and written language).").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U9-L5', teacher, "Critique (using words and other representations) a statement reporting the results of a vote.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U9-L5', teacher, "Interpret (orally and in writing) voting situations involving two choices through the use of ratios and percentages.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U9-L5', student, "Let's vote and choose a winner!").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G6-U9-L5', "This is the first in a series of optional lessons about voting systems. The activities are about voting on issues where there are two choices. Students use equivalent ratio concepts and skills developed in grade 6 to compare voting results of two groups, to determine whether an issue wins an election with a supermajority rule, and discover that a few people can determine the results of an election when very few people vote.").
