vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G6-U9-L6', "This lesson reveals that voting rules shape outcomes—plurality winners needn't have majority support—and that ranked-choice voting can overturn plurality results. Students often assume 'most votes' equals fairness; the cognitive demand of tracking preferences across multiple elimination rounds is where they typically falter.").

vision_lesson('IM-G6-U9-L7', 6, 9, 7, "Comparing Voting Systems").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U9-L7', teacher, "Choose and justify (orally) which voting system seems the fairest for dealing with more than two choices.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U9-L7', teacher, "Compare and contrast (orally and in writing) different voting systems for dealing with more than two choices, i.e., plurality, runoff, and instant runoff.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U9-L7', teacher, "Interpret (orally and in writing) voting situations involving two choices, through the use of ratios and percentages.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U9-L7', student, "Let's compare voting systems.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G6-U9-L7', "This optional lesson continues to explore the effects of different voting systems when there are more than two options. Students explore an instant runoff voting system and compare it to the plurality, runoff, and ranked voting systems from the earlier lesson. While comparing and analyzing the results of each system, students reason abstractly and quantitatively (MP2). Students also analyze the effectiveness of the election models (MP4).").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U9-L7', building_on, '6.RP.A.3').
