vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G6-U9-L8', "This lesson surfaces the core tension: proportionality mathematics produces non-integer quotients (2.5 children per computer, 0.1 advisors), but real representation demands whole people. Students discover that perfect fairness is mathematically impossible when you can't divide a representative. The critical insight—that equal treatment at the ratio level (e.g., 85 students per advisor) still creates unequal treatment at the allocation level (Trombone Academy gets one advisor for 10 students, Dr. King gets one for 83)—lives outside any arithmetic model and requires judgment about what \"fair\" ev").

vision_lesson('IM-G6-U9-L9', 6, 9, 9, "Designing Districts").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U9-L9', teacher, "Compare and contrast different ways to distribute representatives.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U9-L9', teacher, "Describe (using words and other representations) how changing the way votes are grouped can affect the outcome.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G6-U9-L9', student, "Let's design districts.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G6-U9-L9', "In this optional lesson, students investigate how districts can be designed to influence the outcome of an election. Students are asked to gerrymander several districts: to divide them into sections to influence the final voting result in opposite ways. The mathematics here involves geometric properties of shapes on maps: area and connectedness, as well as some proportional reasoning. Most of the activities use students' skills from earlier units to reason abstractly and quantitatively about ratios and proportional relationships in the context of real-world problems (MP2). While some of the activities do not involve much computation, they will require serious thinking and decision making as students construct arguments and justify their plans (MP3).").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U9-L9', addressing, '6.RP.A.3').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G6-U9-L9', addressing, '6.RP.A.3.c').
