vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U9-L10', "rectangle_decomposition_to_squares", "Three 5×5 squares and five 1×1 squares; side lengths 5, 5, 5, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1", 'Activity 10.1, problem 3', "81", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G6-U9-L10', "improper_fraction_to_mixed_number", "3 1/5", 'Activity 10.2, problem 3a', "84", text).
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G6-U9-L10', "Rectangle decomposition exposes the greatest common factor through the smallest square's side length. Students often miss that this GCF directly simplifies the fraction formed by the rectangle's dimensions—for a 28×12 rectangle, the smallest square has side 4 (the GCF), which reduces 28/12 to 7/3. The algorithm mirrors the Euclidean GCD procedure geometrically.").

