vision_lesson_computation('IM-G7-U1-L4', "corresponding_distances_MNOP_QRST", "MNOP: MO = 6, NP = 9; QRST: QS = 4, RT = 6", 'Activity 4.3, Question 2', "98", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G7-U1-L4', "angle_measurement_MNOP_QRST", "angle M = 100°, angle Q = 125°; angle N = 40°, angle S = 40°; angle O = 75°, angle R = 75°; angle P = 140°, angle T = 115°", 'Activity 4.3, Question 3', "98", figure).
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G7-U1-L4', "To determine whether a figure is a scaled copy, students must verify TWO independent conditions: all corresponding angles must be equal in measure, AND all corresponding distances (not just side lengths) must be related by the same scale factor. The most common error is assuming that equal corresponding angles alone prove scaling, or that proportional side lengths suffice. Students also struggle with protractor measurement precision and identifying corresponding distances that do not form sides of the polygons.").

vision_lesson('IM-G7-U1-L5', 7, 1, 5, "The Size of the Scale Factor").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U1-L5', teacher, "Describe (orally and in writing) how scale factors of 1, less than 1, and greater than 1 affect the size of scaled copies.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U1-L5', teacher, "Explain and show (orally and in writing) how to recreate the original figure given a scaled copy and its scale factor.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U1-L5', teacher, "Recognize (orally and in writing) the relationship between a scale factor of a scaled copy to its original figure is the reciprocal of the scale factor of the original figure to its scaled copy.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U1-L5', student, "Let's look at the effects of different scale factors.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G7-U1-L5', "In this lesson, students deepen their understanding of scale factors in two ways: (1) they classify scale factors by size (less than 1, exactly 1, and greater than 1) and notice how each class of factors affects the scaled copies; (2) they see that the scale factor taking an original figure to its copy and the one taking the copy to the original are reciprocals, meaning scaling is reversible—if Figure B is a scaled copy of Figure A, then Figure A is also a scaled copy of Figure B.").
