vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G7-U1-L6', "The core obstacle is that students often assume areas scale at the same rate as side lengths (linearly), when in fact areas scale by the square of the scale factor. Hands-on pattern-block building makes this distinction concrete, but students need repeated exposure to coordinate 1-dimensional (side length) and 2-dimensional (area) scaling before the pattern generalizes.").

vision_lesson('IM-G7-U1-L7', 7, 1, 7, "Scale Drawings").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U1-L7', teacher, "I can explain what a scale drawing is, and I can explain what its scale means.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U1-L7', teacher, "I can use actual distances and a scale to find scaled distances.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U1-L7', teacher, "I can use a scale drawing and its scale to find actual distances.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U1-L7', student, "Let's explore scale drawings.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G7-U1-L7', "In this lesson, students begin to look at scale drawings, or scaled two-dimensional representations of actual objects or places. Students see that although scale drawings capture three-dimensional objects or places, they show scaled measurements in only two of the dimensions, and that all information is projected onto a plane. They see that the principles and strategies they used when reasoning about scaled copies are applicable to scale drawings. Students work with drawings where the scale is given in words and where the scale is shown as a line segment. As students use scales and scale drawings to find actual and scaled lengths, they reason quantitatively and abstractly.").
