vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G7-U1-L8', "This lesson uses maps and graphic scales as concrete tools to solve problems about speed, distance, and time—situations students find accessible but cognitively demanding. The main challenge is that roads curve and don't measure straight, so students must estimate distances and accept approximate answers rather than seeking precision. A second trap: students often confuse which quantity to solve for (speed vs. distance vs. time) and may forget to convert units (minutes to hours, feet to miles). The lesson does not formalise the d = rt equation, though some students may discover it; reasoning h").

vision_lesson('IM-G7-U1-L9', 7, 1, 9, "Creating Scale Drawings").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U1-L9', teacher, "I can determine the scale of a scale drawing when I know lengths on the drawing and corresponding actual lengths.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U1-L9', teacher, "I know how different scales affect the lengths in the scale drawing.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U1-L9', teacher, "When I know the actual measurements, I can create a scale drawing at a given scale.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U1-L9', student, "Let's create our own scale drawings.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G7-U1-L9', "In this lesson, students use actual distances to calculate scaled distances and create their own scale drawings. Next, they see how different scale drawings can be created of the same actual thing, using different scales. They also see how the choice of scale influences the drawing. For example, a scale drawing with a scale of 1 cm to 5 m will be smaller than a scale drawing of the same object with a scale of 1 cm to 2 m. (Since each centimeter represents a larger distance, it takes fewer centimeters to represent the object.) This prepares students for future lessons in which they will recreate a given scale drawing at a different scale. Noticing how scale drawings change with the choice of scale develops important structural understanding of scale drawings (MP7).").
