vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G7-U1-L10', "This lesson hinges on two interrelated concepts that many seventh graders find counterintuitive: (1) when you change to a smaller scale (representing more actual distance per drawing unit), the drawing itself becomes larger, and (2) area scales by the square of the linear factor, not linearly. Students frequently confuse linear scaling with area scaling—for instance, mistaking a 1.5-fold linear enlargement for a 1.5-fold area enlargement rather than 2.25-fold—or they may assume that both drawings must be the same physical size if they represent the same object.").

vision_lesson('IM-G7-U1-L11', 7, 1, 11, "Scales without Units").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U1-L11', teacher, "Explain (orally and in writing) how to use scales without units to determine scaled or actual distances.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U1-L11', teacher, "Interpret scales expressed without units, e.g., \"1 to 50,\" (in spoken and written language).").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U1-L11', student, "Let's explore a different way to express scales.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G7-U1-L11', "In this lesson, students see that a scale can be expressed without units. For example, the scale \"1 to 60\" means that every length on the scale drawing represents an actual length that is 60 times its size, whatever the unit may be (inches, centimeters, etc.). Expressing the scale without units, such as \"1 to 60,\" highlights the scale factor that relates the scale drawing to the actual object. Each measurement on the scale drawing is multiplied by 60 to find the corresponding measurement on the actual object. This relates closely to the scaled copies examined earlier in the unit in which each copy was related to the original by a scale factor. Students gain a better understanding of both scaled copies and scale drawings as they recognize the common underlying structure.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G7-U1-L11', addressing, '7.G.A.1').
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G7-U1-L11', "interpret_scale_without_units", "The scale 1 to 100 means actual distances are 100 times the distances on the map.", 'Warm-up (Activity 11.1)', "205", text).
