vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G7-U2-L9', "All eight arithmetic task-events map to real automata: the unit-rate divisions (comments-per-minute: 1325/5, 800/3, 50000/210) are partitive and map to fair_share_equal_groups (first pass had these as measure_groups_of_size, which is wrong — they distribute a total across a known number of minute-groups to find the per-minute size); the Info Gap time divisions (9000/300, 8000/250) are quotitive and correctly measure_groups_of_size (how many minute-sized meter-chunks fit); the rate*time products are repeat_equal_groups. The lesson's central demand, though — judging whether a situation is propor").

vision_lesson('IM-G7-U2-L10', 7, 2, 10, "Introducing Graphs of Proportional Relationships").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U2-L10', teacher, "Compare and contrast (orally) graphs of relationships.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U2-L10', teacher, "Generalize (orally and in writing) that a proportional relationship can be represented in the coordinate plane by a line that includes the \"origin\" or by a collection of points that lie on such a line.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U2-L10', teacher, "Justify (orally) that a table and a graph represent the same relationship.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U2-L10', student, "Let's see how graphs of proportional relationships differ from graphs of other relationships.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G7-U2-L10', "This lesson introduces an important way of representing a proportional relationship: its graph. Students plot points on the graph from tables, and, by the end of the lesson, start to see that the graph of a proportional relationship always lies on a line that passes through the origin. (0, 0). (They will be able to explain why this is true in grade 8.) They match tables and graphs of given situations and articulate their reasons for each match (MP3).").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G7-U2-L10', building_on, '5.G.A').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G7-U2-L10', building_on, '6.NS.C.8').
