vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G7-U2-L11', "Page 186 is the cool-down (\"Responding to Student Thinking / Press Pause\") page for Lesson 11, not the full lesson. It shows a distance-time proportional graph for a cyclist with the labeled point (4, 1 1/3) = (4, 4/3). Task (a) asks students to interpret that point qualitatively (\"It takes her 4 minutes to travel 1 1/3 miles\") — interpretation only, not recorded as an arithmetic event. Task (b) asks students to find the constant of proportionality; the printed solution states it is 1/3, \"seen on the graph at the point (1, 1/3)\". VERIFIED NUMBERS: the operands 4/3 and 4 are read directly from").

vision_lesson('IM-G7-U2-L12', 7, 2, 12, "Using Graphs to Compare Relationships").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U2-L12', teacher, "I can compare two, related proportional relationships based on their graphs.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U2-L12', teacher, "I know that the steeper graph of two proportional relationships has a larger constant of proportionality.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U2-L12', student, "Let's graph more than one relationship on the same grid.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G7-U2-L12', "In this lesson, students examine graphs that have multiple proportional relationships presented on the same set of axes. They compare and interpret the steepness of each graph in terms of the context. First, students use distance-versus-time graphs to decide which person from a group is going the fastest. They then work with graphs where the scale is not specified on each axis and realize that they can still use the structure of such graphs to compare rates (MP7).").
