vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G7-U2-L12', "The lesson centers on proportional relationships, mostly through graphical interpretation; the demanded arithmetic is division, used both to express quotients as fractions/decimals (warm-up) and to compute constants of proportionality (rates = distance/time) in the activity and practice. Kinds are not uniform: the warm-up's opening item (3 divided by 6) reads most naturally as partitive fair_share_equal_groups, matching its sample reasoning (\"divide 3 wholes into 6 groups\"); the remaining quotients and every rate computation are cast as inverse_fact_decomposition, since the lesson frames each").

vision_lesson('IM-G7-U2-L13', 7, 2, 13, "Two Graphs for Each Relationship").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U2-L13', teacher, "I can interpret a graph of a proportional relationship using the situation.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U2-L13', teacher, "I can write an equation representing a proportional relationship from a graph.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U2-L13', student, "Let's use tables, equations, and graphs to answer questions about proportional relationships.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G7-U2-L13', "In this lesson, students make connections between tables, equations, and graphs that represent the same proportional relationship. They start with an activity designed to help them see the different ways in which the structure of the graph and the equation are connected. For example, the coordinates for any point (a, b) on the graph can be divided to find the constant of proportionality k = b/a in the equation. This work prepares students for seeing two ways to graph a proportional relationship, depending on which quantity goes on which axis, and understanding that the constants of proportionality in the two ways are reciprocals.").
