vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G7-U3-L1', "This lesson teaches students to use quotient calculations and visual inspection of graphs to determine whether real-world measurements might represent a proportional relationship, accounting for measurement error. The central insight is distinguishing relationships that are proportional despite measurement noise (diagonal and perimeter, quotient ≈ 2.8) from those that are genuinely non-proportional (diagonal and area, variable quotients). Students often struggle to accept that small inconsistencies in data might be explained by measurement error rather than indicating a non-proportional relati").

vision_lesson('IM-G7-U3-L2', 7, 3, 2, "Exploring Circles").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U3-L2', teacher, "Compare (orally) different ways to measure a circle, and generalize the relationship between radius and diameter.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U3-L2', teacher, "Comprehend the terms \"diameter,\" \"center,\" \"radius,\" and \"circumference\" in reference to parts of a circle.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U3-L2', teacher, "Describe (orally and in writing) the defining characteristics of a circle.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U3-L2', student, "Let's explore circles.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G7-U3-L2', "In this lesson, students learn vocabulary for describing circles precisely (MP6). Students move from the informal idea of a circle as a \\\"round figure\\\" to the more formal definition that a circle is the set of points that are equally distant from the center, enclosing a circular region.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G7-U3-L2', addressing, '7.G.A').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G7-U3-L2', addressing, '7.G.A.2').
