vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G7-U3-L2', "This lesson formalizes what a circle IS—the set of points equidistant from a center—and introduces precise vocabulary (radius, diameter, circumference, center). Students commonly confuse circles with circular objects, mistake 3D shapes' circular cross-sections for mathematical circles, or struggle to identify which part of a circle (diameter, radius, or circumference) is being measured. The key relationship to establish here is diameter = 2 × radius, which scaffolds circumference and area work in later lessons.").

vision_lesson('IM-G7-U3-L3', 7, 3, 3, "Exploring Circumference").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U3-L3', teacher, "Comprehend the word \"pi\" and the symbol π to refer to the constant of proportionality between the diameter and circumference of a circle.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U3-L3', teacher, "Create and describe (in writing) graphs that show measurements of circles.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U3-L3', teacher, "Generalize that the relationship between diameter and circumference is proportional and that the constant of proportionality is a little more than 3.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U3-L3', student, "Let's explore the circumference of circles.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G7-U3-L3', "In this lesson, students discover that there is a proportional relationship between the diameter and circumference of a circle. They use their knowledge from the previous unit on proportionality to estimate the constant of proportionality. Then they use the constant to compute the circumference given the diameter (and vice versa) for different circles. Students learn that pi (π) is the value of the constant and discuss various commonly used approximations. Students will relate the circumference to the radius in a future lesson, so it is not necessary to do so in this lesson.").
