vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G7-U3-L3', "This lesson introduces π as the constant of proportionality between diameter and circumference through hands-on measurement and graphing. Main challenges: accurate measurement of real circular objects (students often measure diameter without crossing the widest point or wrap string loosely around the circumference), and correct application of the proportional formula—students frequently confuse whether to multiply diameter by π to find circumference or divide circumference by π to find diameter. The concept of π itself remains approximate (3.1, 3.14, etc.) in this lesson; the infinite, non-rep").

vision_lesson('IM-G7-U3-L4', 7, 3, 4, "Applying Circumference").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U3-L4', teacher, "Compare and contrast (orally) values for the same measurements that were calculated using different approximations for π.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U3-L4', teacher, "Explain (orally) how to calculate the radius, diameter, or circumference of a circle, given one of these three measurements.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U3-L4', student, "Let's use π to solve problems.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G7-U3-L4', "Students apply the relationships between diameter, radius, and circumference to solve problems in a variety of contexts, developing flexibility with the relationships rather than memorizing formulas. They solve problems about distances of paths composed of multiple circles or parts of circles and decompose complex shapes strategically (MP1), choosing appropriate levels of precision for π and calculations (MP6). Understanding C = 2πr prepares the transition to area in future lessons.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G7-U3-L4', addressing, '7.G.B.4').
