vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G7-U3-L4', "Applying circumference flexibly—moving between radius, diameter, and circumference using C = 2πr—is the core skill. Students commonly confuse radius and diameter, apply different π approximations without understanding when each is appropriate, and struggle to judge how much precision makes sense given their measurements. They also find it difficult to decompose composite figures (track = rectangle + two semicircles) and may mistakenly apply the full-circle formula when only arcs are involved.").

vision_lesson('IM-G7-U3-L5', 7, 3, 5, "Circumference and Wheels").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U3-L5', teacher, "Compare wheels of different sizes and explain why a larger wheel needs fewer rotations to travel the same distance").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U3-L5', teacher, "Generalize that the distance a wheel rolls in one rotation is equal to the circumference of the wheel").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U3-L5', teacher, "Write an equation to represent the proportional relationship between the number of rotations and the distance a wheel travels").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U3-L5', student, "Let's explore how far different wheels roll.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G7-U3-L5', "This optional lesson extends students' understanding of circumference by exploring proportional relationships related to how far a wheel travels when it rolls. Students discover that the distance a wheel travels in one complete rotation equals the wheel's circumference, and that the total distance traveled is proportional to the number of rotations. The relationship is foundational for understanding how odometers and speedometers work in vehicles. Students use quantitative and abstract reasoning to represent the relationship with an equation and apply unit conversions to solve problems involving rotational speed and linear distance.").
