vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G7-U3-L7', "This page is an assessment checkpoint, not the full lesson. Students apply A = πr² to find the area of a fractional region of a circle. Critical misconception: students often compute the full circle area (36π) instead of recognizing the shaded region is one quarter, or confuse radius (6) with diameter (12) and use 6 as the diameter.").

vision_lesson('IM-G7-U3-L8', 7, 3, 8, "Relating Area to Circumference").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U3-L8', teacher, "Generalize a process for finding the area of a circle, and justify (orally) why this can be abstracted as πr².").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U3-L8', teacher, "Show how a circle can be decomposed and rearranged to approximate a polygon, and justify (orally and in writing) that the area of this polygon is equal to half the circle's circumference multiplied by its radius.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U3-L8', student, "Let's rearrange circles to calculate their areas.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G7-U3-L8', "In this lesson, students see that the area of a circle can be found by multiplying πr². They look at informal dissection arguments to derive that relationship. First, students cut and rearrange a circle into a shape that approximates a parallelogram. The next activity is optional because it shows a different way to cut and rearrange a circle into a shape that approximates a triangle. In each case, the area of the polygon is equal to ½ · circumference · radius. Using algebraic reasoning, students construct and critique arguments that this is equivalent to πr · r or πr².").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G7-U3-L8', addressing, '7.G.B.4').
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G7-U3-L8', "estimate_circular_field_area", "About 480,000 m² to 520,000 m² (approximately 80% of surrounding square's 640,000 m²)", 'Activity 8.1 (Warm-up)', "152-153", figure).
