vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G7-U3-L9', "Students learn to find areas of composite figures by recognizing which regions are circles, semicircles, or quarter-circles, then decomposing the shape accordingly. The core challenge is visual decomposition from diagrams where radius must be inferred (often unmarked). Common misconceptions: students confuse the number of parts with the area itself (e.g., assuming four equal circles must sum to an area equal to a unit square times four); they struggle to distinguish quarter-circles from unit squares; and they often want to apply simple circle formulas (like \"half the perimeter times the radius").

vision_lesson('IM-G7-U3-L10', 7, 3, 10, "Distinguishing Circumference and Area").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U3-L10', teacher, "Critique (orally and in writing) claims about the radius, diameter, circumference, or area of a circle in a real-world situation.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U3-L10', teacher, "Decide whether to calculate the circumference or area of a circle to solve a problem in a real-world situation, and justify (orally and in writing) the decision.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U3-L10', teacher, "Estimate measurements of a circle in a real-world situation, and explain (orally and in writing) the estimation strategy.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U3-L10', student, "Let's contrast circumference and area.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G7-U3-L10', "In this lesson, students apply what they have learned about circumference and area of circles to solve problems in context. Both types of problems are mixed together so students have to determine which measurement is called for in each problem situation (MP2). Students continue working with answers expressed in terms of π. Also, in previous lessons students were always given one measurement of each circle, but in this lesson they must rely on their own estimations to solve the problems (MP6).").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G7-U3-L10', addressing, '7.G.B.4').
