vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G7-U3-L10', "Students must distinguish between circumference (linear distance around) and area (region inside) contextually and judge whether their estimates are reasonable. The common confusion is conflating linear and square units, or applying the wrong measurement type to a problem when both are plausible mathematically.").

vision_lesson('IM-G7-U3-L11', 7, 3, 11, "Stained-Glass Windows").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U3-L11', teacher, "Apply circumference and area of circles to calculate the cost of a stained-glass window, and explain (orally and in writing) the solution method.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U3-L11', teacher, "Design a stained-glass window that could be built for a given dollar amount, and present (orally, in writing, and through other representations) a justification that it costs less than the limit.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U3-L11', teacher, "Make simplifying assumptions to solve problems about a stained-glass window.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U3-L11', student, "Let's use circumference and area to design stained-glass windows.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G7-U3-L11', "This culminating lesson is optional. Students work on several tasks that combine circumference and area ideas and computations. First, students are given a design for a stained-glass window and the prices of different components, then decide if it is possible to produce the window for a certain amount of money while making assumptions about the shapes in the design and how materials are sold. Optional activities include calculating how scaling the window affects the cost (bringing in ideas from a previous unit, where the total cost does not simply increase by the scale factor nor by its square), and inventing their own stained-glass window design for a given cost constraint. The series of tasks provides many opportunities to engage in mathematical modeling.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G7-U3-L11', addressing, '7.EE.B.3').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G7-U3-L11', addressing, '7.G.A.1').
