vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G7-U4-L12', "Most of this lesson asks students to find what percent one dollar amount is of another: divide(4,46) gives Andre's 8.7% savings, and the same shape recurs in divide(693.50,18250), divide(6.25,33.75), divide(80,375), divide(547,513), divide(7.77,42), and divide(100,75). The elementary vocabulary has no automaton that reads a quotient as a percentage, so those carry kind NONE. Recovering an original amount by dividing out a percent factor, divide(104,1.3)=80, sits outside the base-ten and fraction strategies for the same reason. What the model does cover is the multiplications by a known decimal").

vision_lesson('IM-G7-U4-L13', 7, 4, 13, "Measurement Error").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U4-L13', teacher, "Compare and contrast (orally) multiple measurements of the same length that result from using rulers with different levels of precision.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U4-L13', teacher, "Describe (orally) possible sources of \"measurement error\" when measuring lengths.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U4-L13', teacher, "Generalize a process for calculating measurement error and expressing it as a percentage of the actual length.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U4-L13', student, "Let's use percentages to describe how accurately we can measure.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G7-U4-L13', "In this lesson, students express measurement error as a percentage of the correct amount. Measurement error is the positive difference between a measured amount and the actual amount. Students see how measurement error can arise in two different ways: from the level of precision in the measurement device and from human error.").
