vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G7-U4-L14', "Percent-error work here demands two kinds of arithmetic that sit above the vocabulary's automata. (1) Dividing an error by an actual amount and \"what percent of\" divisions (0.2÷3.5, 514÷2486, 25÷0.84, 3÷6) produce ratios/percentages no single division automaton names — division by a decimal (63÷1.05, 25÷0.84) likewise — so their kind is NONE. (2) Whole-number-times-decimal percent products (1.5%×10/12/14/16 ft, 48×0.8) do map to decimal_multiplication_rule. The plant problem (3/4 cup increased by 25% = 15/16 cup) is a percent increase on a fractional quantity with no clean automaton, kind NONE").

vision_lesson('IM-G7-U4-L15', 7, 4, 15, "Changes on the Earth").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U4-L15', teacher, "Calculate a percent increase or decrease, and interpret (orally and in writing) its meaning in the situation.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U4-L15', student, "Let's use percentages to make sense of changes on Earth.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G7-U4-L15', "This lesson is optional. In this lesson, students calculate percentages of increase or decrease based on information about how some different places on Earth have changed over time. Students choose what pairs of values to compare to make sense of the situation (MP1). Students attend to precision of language as they calculate and report values to describe these changes. (MP6).").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G7-U4-L15', addressing, '7.RP.A.3').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G7-U4-L15', building_toward, '7.RP.A.3').
