vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G7-U4-L15', "This lesson directly addresses 7.RP.A.3 (percent increase/decrease calculations). The computational tasks require ratio/proportion operations—finding a change as a percentage of an original value, and applying a percent increase as a multiplicative factor—that fall outside the current model vocabulary. While component operations (subtraction, division, multiplication) appear in the vocabulary, the integrated percent-calculation strategy is not represented. Students are asked to calculate percentages and apply growth factors, both of which are domain-specific skills beyond basic arithmetic.").

vision_lesson('IM-G7-U4-L16', 7, 4, 16, "Posing Percentage Problems").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U4-L16', teacher, "Generate questions (orally and in writing) about a real-world situation involving percent increase or decrease.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U4-L16', teacher, "Interpret news headlines or advertisements that include statements about percent increase and decrease.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U4-L16', teacher, "Solve a problem about a real-world situation involving percent increase or decrease and present the solution method (in writing and through other representations).").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U4-L16', student, "Let's explore how percentages are used in the news.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G7-U4-L16', "In this culminating lesson on percentages, students work in groups to examine news clippings that mention percentages and sort them according to whether they are about percent increase or percent decrease. Then they formulate questions about the situations and share their questions with other groups in a gallery walk. As students make sense of what information is given in the clipping and what information they could ask for in a question, they are reasoning quantitatively and abstractly (MP2).").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G7-U4-L16', addressing, '7.RP.A.3').
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G7-U4-L16', "This lesson is a culminating activity focused on interpretation, question-posing, and presentation of real-world percentage scenarios rather than computation. Students generate their own questions and solve their own student-crafted problems based on teacher-provided news clippings. No concrete arithmetic problems with specific operands are prescribed by the lesson itself. All three activities (Sorting the News, Investigating, Displaying the News) have responses marked \"Answers vary\" because the computational work is student-generated and context-dependent.").

vision_lesson('IM-G7-U5-L1', 7, 5, 1, "Interpreting Negative Numbers").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U5-L1', teacher, "Interpret signed numbers in the contexts of temperature and elevation.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U5-L1', teacher, "Order rational numbers, and justify (orally) the comparisons.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U5-L1', teacher, "Plot points on a vertical or horizontal number line to represent rational numbers.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U5-L1', student, "Let's review what we know about signed numbers.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G7-U5-L1', "In this lesson, students review what they learned previously about positive and negative numbers. They remember that negative numbers are less than 0 degrees, while positive numbers are greater than 0 degrees. First, students look at thermometers, reading temperatures above and below zero and comparing them. Next, they examine the vertical position of animals above or below sea level and describe the vertical distances between them. Both activities involve a number line that is oriented vertically to help students make sense of the context. As students relate the relative position of numbers on the number line to the meaning of \"above zero\" and \"below zero\" in each context, they are reasoning abstractly and quantitatively (MP2).").
