vision_lesson('IM-G7-U5-L5', 7, 5, 5, "Representing Subtraction").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U5-L5', teacher, "Generalize (orally and in writing) that subtracting a number results in the same value as adding the additive inverse.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U5-L5', teacher, "Interpret a number line diagram that represents subtracting signed numbers as adding with an unknown addend.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U5-L5', teacher, "Use a number line diagram to find the difference of signed numbers, and explain (orally) the reasoning.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U5-L5', student, "Let's subtract signed numbers.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G7-U5-L5', "In this lesson, students make sense of subtracting signed numbers by representing it on the number line. First, they rewrite subtraction equations as addition equations with an unknown addend—for example, -8 - 3 = ? can be thought of as 3 + ? = -8. Students represent these equations on a number line and find the unknown value—to get from 3 to -8, the second arrow must be 11 units long and pointing left, so ? = -11. From such examples, students generalize that subtracting a number gets the same value as adding its opposite—in this case, -8 - 3 and -8 + (-3) are both equal to -11. As students use the results from multiple subtraction expressions to notice a general pattern, they are making use of repeated reasoning (MP8).").
