vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G7-U5-L7', "All core arithmetic is addition and subtraction of signed rational numbers. Tasks map to four automata: signed_addition_with_sign_relation (combining signed quantities into a total), compare_by_matching_difference (the difference between two known quantities, signed), count_up_missing_addend (recovering an unknown starting state from an end state plus a net change — the day-4 Kilimanjaro problem, start+91=3986), and decimal_addition_by_aligned_units (summing two positive decimals, 0.86+1.57, where no sign relation is exercised). The vocabulary has no dedicated signed-subtraction automaton; sub").

vision_lesson('IM-G7-U5-L8', 7, 5, 8, "Multiplying Rational Numbers (Part 1)").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U5-L8', teacher, "Explain (orally and in writing) how signed numbers can be used to represent positions and speeds in opposite directions.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U5-L8', teacher, "Generalize (orally) that the product of a negative number and a positive number is negative.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U5-L8', teacher, "Write a multiplication equation to represent a situation involving constant speed with direction.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U5-L8', student, "Let's use signed numbers to represent movement.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G7-U5-L8', "Students explore multiplying a negative number by a positive number using the context of constant velocity. Using a chosen zero point, a positive/negative convention for direction along a number line, and a description of movement, they reason about why the product of a negative velocity and a positive travel time gives a negative position. Across several velocities and times they generalize about the sign of the product, then apply the same reasoning to carbon dioxide released (positive) or absorbed (negative) by cars, trees, and clams over a year.").
