vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G7-U5-L15', "The lesson's core demand — solving linear equations of the form x + p = q and px = q where p, q, and x are rational (often negative) — turns on additive and multiplicative inverses: adding the opposite of p, or multiplying by the reciprocal of p. The strategy vocabulary has no automaton for the reciprocal-based solution of a fractional-coefficient equation, so 1/2 x = -5, -2x = -9, 2/5 t = 6, 2/3 c = 32, and 8x = -5 all carry kind NONE. It also lacks a signed-division automaton: -2x = -9, -2x = 7, and -12 = -3y demand dividing signed quantities and fall to NONE as well. Where solving reduces t").

vision_lesson('IM-G7-U5-L16', 7, 5, 16, "Representing Contexts with Equations").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U5-L16', teacher, "Coordinate (orally and in writing) verbal descriptions, equations, and diagrams that represent the same situation involving an unknown amount in the context of temperature or elevation.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U5-L16', teacher, "Write equations of the form x + p = q or px = q to represent and solve a problem in an unfamiliar context, and present the solution method (using words and other representations).").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U5-L16', student, "Let's write equations that represent situations.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G7-U5-L16', "In this lesson, students consolidate their understanding of solving equations of the form x + p = q or px = q, where p, q, and x are rational numbers. Students choose equations that represent a context and solve it. They critique an incorrectly solved equation and construct an explanation about a correct solution (MP3). In the optional activities, students create their own equations for situations and solve them, reasoning quantitatively and abstractly as they relate the situation to the variables, terms, and operations in their equations (MP2).").
