vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G7-U6-L2', "This lesson teaches tape diagrams as a visual tool for modeling situations with equal groups and sequential operations (like adding to each group). The key challenge is understanding that a single variable must represent the same unknown quantity every time it appears in a diagram, AND that expressions like (y + 2) can label segments to show how an amount changes. Students often think separate diagrams are needed to show sequential actions; they need to see how one variable and one expression can capture the full situation.").

vision_lesson('IM-G7-U6-L3', 7, 6, 3, "Reasoning about Equations with Tape Diagrams").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U6-L3', teacher, "Coordinate tape diagrams and equations of the form px + q = r or p(x + q) = r.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U6-L3', teacher, "Create a tape diagram to represent an equation of the form px + q = r or p(x + q) = r, and use it to solve the equation.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U6-L3', teacher, "Identify equivalent equations, and justify (using words and other representations) that they are equivalent.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U6-L3', student, "Let's see how equations can describe tape diagrams.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G7-U6-L3', "The purpose of this lesson is to make connections between a tape diagram and an equation of the form px + q = r or p(x + q) = r. Students match tape diagrams to corresponding equations and sort them into categories. Then they draw tape diagrams to represent equations. Students use the tape diagram and the equation to reason about a solution, but this is not the time to teach particular methods for solving such equations. At this point in the unit, students should reason using any method that makes sense to them.").
