vision_lesson_computation('IM-G7-U6-L14', "Calculate the marginal cost (cost of one additional sandwich unit)", "$6", 'Problem 5b, page 61', "61", text).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G7-U6-L14', "Identify which word problem cannot be modeled by the equation 3x = 27", "C (Diego's pizza pricing involves a fixed delivery fee, so cost is not purely proportional to quantity)", 'Problem 6, page 61', "61", text).
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G7-U6-L14', "The central misconception: students assume any regular linear pattern is proportional without verifying that unit rates remain constant. In Problem 5, both prices increase regularly with quantity, but the unit rates diverge ($6.67 vs $6.50), revealing a fixed fee ($2 delivery charge). For Problem 6, students often try to force contexts into simple proportional equations without recognizing that fixed-cost structures demand a different model. This lesson demands careful verification of proportionality claims, not just visual pattern recognition.\"").

