vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G7-U6-L20', "This lesson focuses on combining like terms to write simpler equivalent expressions. The central misconception to watch: students often believe two expressions are equivalent because they equal the same value when they substitute a single test number (e.g., both expressions equal 10 when x = 1), but true equivalence must hold for all values. The lesson insists students use algebraic properties (distributive, associative, commutative) to justify equivalence, not just numerical testing.").

