vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G7-U6-L21', "The lesson's central challenge is correctly applying the distributive property and handling the subtraction sign in front of parentheses. Students commonly distribute only to the first term inside parentheses, or forget that a negative sign applies to all terms being subtracted, leading to incorrect simplifications like 8 - 3(4 - 9x) = 20 - 45x instead of the correct -4 + 27x.").

vision_lesson('IM-G7-U6-L22', 7, 6, 22, "Applications of Expressions").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U6-L22', teacher, "Determine which order for applying multiple coupons gives the better discount and explain (orally and in writing) the reasoning.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U6-L22', teacher, "Justify (orally, in writing, and using other representations) that two different sequences of calculations give the same result.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U6-L22', student, "Let's use expressions to solve problems.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G7-U6-L22', "In this culminating lesson, students look at several real-world situations that can be represented by an expression with a variable. First, students write expressions to represent two different methods for performing a real-world calculation. They use the expressions to show why the two methods are equivalent. Then students are presented with two different coupons to a store (a 20% off coupon and a $30 off coupon). They apply their understanding of expressions, equations, and inequalities to decide in which order the coupons should be applied to save more money on a purchase.").
