vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G7-U7-L5', "Students must recognize which angles form complementary (90°), supplementary (180°), or vertical (equal) relationships from a diagram of intersecting lines, write equations expressing those relationships, and solve the equations. The core challenge is the translation from visual geometry to algebraic form—students frequently misidentify which angles relate, write equations that don't capture the geometric constraint, or make solving errors. Vertical angles are typically recognized as a property (b = 27°) rather than solved via equation.").

vision_lesson('IM-G7-U7-L6', 7, 7, 6, "Building Polygons (Part 1)").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U7-L6', teacher, "I can show that the 3 side lengths that form a triangle cannot be rearranged to form a different triangle.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U7-L6', teacher, "I can show that the 4 side lengths that form a quadrilateral can be rearranged to form different quadrilaterals.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U7-L6', student, "Let's build shapes.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G7-U7-L6', "This lesson is the first in a series of lessons in which students create shapes with given conditions. Students experiment with making polygons of various numbers and combinations of side lengths using cardboard strips and metal fasteners. The goal is for students to make sense of the different shapes that are possible under given constraints about side lengths, including whether only one shape is possible or no shape is possible. Students do not try to formulate general rules about what side lengths are possible; in the next lesson, they formulate such a rule for triangles.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G7-U7-L6', addressing, '7.G.A.2').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G7-U7-L6', building_toward, '7.G.A.2').
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G7-U7-L6', "The lesson's central finding—that three side lengths uniquely determine a triangle but four side lengths do not uniquely determine a quadrilateral—contradicts students' intuition that specifying all dimensions fixes a shape. Students often assume their quadrilateral is wrong when it differs from a classmate's version with identical side lengths; the lesson reveals both are valid. This geometric rigidity versus flexibility emerges from physical construction before any abstract reasoning about constraints.").

vision_lesson('IM-G7-U7-L7', 7, 7, 7, "Using Equations to Solve for Unknown Angles").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U7-L7', teacher, "Determine whether a given equation represents the relationship between angles shown in a diagram.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U7-L7', teacher, "Solve an equation that represents a relationship between angle measures, and explain (in writing and using other representations) the reasoning.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U7-L7', teacher, "Write an equation of the form px + q = r or p(x + q) = r to represent the relationship between angles in a given diagram.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U7-L7', student, "Let's figure out missing angles using equations.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G7-U7-L7', "In this lesson, students practice writing and solving equations of the form px + q = r in the context of finding unknown angle measures. Students examine the structure of angle relationships as they compare a diagram to possible equations that could be used to represent the angle relationships. The angles used connect to earlier work with supplementary, complementary, and vertical angles, giving additional opportunities to build fluency with these concepts.").
