vision_lesson('IM-G7-U7-L8', 7, 7, 8, "Triangles with 3 Common Measures").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U7-L8', teacher, "Describe, compare, and contrast (orally and in writing) triangles that share three common measures of angles or sides.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U7-L8', teacher, "Justify (orally and using other representations) whether triangles are identical copies or are \"different\" triangles.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U7-L8', teacher, "Recognize that examining which side lengths and angle measures are adjacent can help determine whether triangles are identical copies.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U7-L8', student, "Let's contrast triangles.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G7-U7-L8', "In this lesson, students examine sets of triangles in which all the triangles share 3 common measures of angles or sides. Students learn to recognize when triangles are \"identical copies\" that are oriented differently on the page, and when they are different triangles (meaning triangles that are not identical copies). This prepares them for trying to draw more than one triangle given 3 measures, in the next lesson.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G7-U7-L8', addressing, '7.G.A.2').
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G7-U7-L8', "This lesson trains students to see that the adjacency and order of side and angle measures determine triangle congruence, not just having three equal measures. The core misconception: students assume any three matching measures make identical triangles, without recognizing that two triangles with sides 5, 7 and a 30° angle can be different if the angle's position relative to the sides differs. Students often miss subtle size differences when the same three measures are arranged in different orders, and may not recognize that tracing, flipping, and rotating are the only ways to verify identical").

vision_lesson('IM-G7-U7-L9', 7, 7, 9, "Drawing Triangles (Part 1)").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U7-L9', teacher, "Draw triangles with two given angle measures and one side length, one given angle measure and two side lengths, or three side lengths").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U7-L9', teacher, "Justify whether 3 measures of angles or sides determine a unique triangle or more than one triangle, or if no triangle is possible").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G7-U7-L9', "This checkpoint assesses student understanding of triangle construction and the conditions under which given measurements determine triangle uniqueness. Students draw triangles from constraints and justify whether the given measures produce one triangle, multiple triangles, or no triangle at all.").
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G7-U7-L9', "construct_triangle_from_three_side_lengths", "A triangle with sides 3 in, 4 in, 6 in", 'Checkpoint Task 1a', "108", text).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G7-U7-L9', "determine_triangle_uniqueness_given_sss", "No. These 3 side lengths make a unique triangle.", 'Checkpoint Task 1b', "108", text).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G7-U7-L9', "determine_triangle_ambiguity_given_ssa", "Yes. The angle position between the two sides vs. adjacent to one side produces different triangles.", 'Checkpoint Task 2', "109", text).
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G7-U7-L9', "This lesson centers on triangle construction constraints and the conditions for uniqueness. The core insight: SSS (three side lengths) always produces a unique triangle, but SSA (two sides and an angle) is ambiguous—students often miss that the angle's location relative to the sides matters critically. Students most commonly assume any three measurements uniquely determine a triangle, overlooking the ambiguous case where an angle's position can yield two distinct triangles.").

vision_lesson('IM-G7-U7-L10', 7, 7, 10, "Drawing Triangles (Part 2)").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U7-L10', teacher, "Draw triangles with two given side lengths and one angle measure or with three given angle measures, and describe (orally) how many different triangles could be drawn with the given conditions.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U7-L10', teacher, "Use drawings to justify (in writing) whether two given side lengths and one angle measure determine one unique triangle.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U7-L10', student, "Let's draw some more triangles.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G7-U7-L10', "In this lesson, students continue their work on drawing triangles with specified angle and side measures. Students focus on drawing a triangle given two side lengths and an angle, and given three angles. They continue to gain experience with a compass, ruler, and protractor. They continue to notice from their drawings when the conditions determine one triangle, more than one, or none, and they increase their precision of language as they describe the conditions to each other (MP6).").
