vision_lesson('IM-G7-U7-L11', 7, 7, 11, "Slicing Solids").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U7-L11', teacher, "Categorize images of planes intersecting pyramids and prisms, and describe (orally) the categories.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U7-L11', teacher, "Comprehend that the term \"cross-section\" (in spoken and written language) refers to the two-dimensional face that results from slicing a three-dimensional figure.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U7-L11', teacher, "Describe, compare, and contrast (orally and in writing) different cross-sections that could result from slicing the same pyramid or prism.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U7-L11', student, "Let's see what shapes you get when you slice a three-dimensional object.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G7-U7-L11', "This lesson introduces the idea that slicing a three-dimensional figure with a plane results in a two-dimensional cross-section. Slicing a fruit or vegetable, dipping it in paint, and stamping it on paper helps students make sense of the two-dimensional face that is created by the slice. Given two-dimensional representations of how objects are sliced, students practice visualizing the three-dimensional figures and the resulting cross-sections.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G7-U7-L11', addressing, '7.G.A.3').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G7-U7-L11', building_toward, '7.G.B.6').
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G7-U7-L11', "This lesson is purely spatial-visualization work with no computational tasks. Students must mentally rotate and slice solids to predict resulting 2D cross-sections—a challenge that the arithmetic model does not address. The physical demonstration (slicing fruit/vegetable and painting the cross-section) is essential; without it, students struggle to visualize the abstraction. Common error: confusing cross-sections or failing to predict that different slice angles produce different 2D shapes.").

