vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G7-U7-L14', "This lesson develops the insight that prisms can be unfolded into nets: lateral faces form a single rectangle (perimeter of base × height) plus two identical bases, enabling efficient calculation without computing each face separately. Students commonly struggle to see why this net method works universally and often confuse surface area (square units) with volume (cubic units), despite the lesson's explicit emphasis on distinguishing these two different measures of three-dimensional objects.").

vision_lesson('IM-G7-U7-L15', 7, 7, 15, "Section B: Drawing Polygons with Given Conditions").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U7-L15', teacher, "Draw triangles with two given angle measures and one side length, one given angle measure and two side lengths, or three side lengths").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U7-L15', teacher, "Justify whether 3 measures of angles or sides determine a unique triangle, more than one triangle, or if no triangle is possible").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U7-L15', student, "Determine what combinations of angle and side measures create unique triangles, and justify your reasoning by constructing triangles under different conditions.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G7-U7-L15', "During these lessons students think about what conditions are needed to determine a unique figure, in preparation for future work with congruence in grade 8 and high school. Students experiment with creating polygons using fixed side lengths, generalize the triangle inequality rule (sum of any 2 side lengths must be greater than the third), and explore when given angle and side combinations create unique triangles versus multiple possible triangles.").
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G7-U7-L15', "This is a conceptual geometry lesson focused on understanding the triangle inequality and conditions for uniqueness, not computational arithmetic. Students work through construction and justification; no specific numerical computations are present on pages 105-107. The key learning involves recognizing that three side lengths, or certain angle-side combinations, determine unique triangles while others do not—foundational reasoning for grade 8 congruence work. IM's formal triangle congruence criteria (SSS, SAS, ASA) are not taught at this stage; students develop intuition through construction.").

vision_lesson('IM-G7-U7-L16', 7, 7, 16, "Applying Volume and Surface Area").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U7-L16', teacher, "Solve problems involving the volume and surface area of children's play structures.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U7-L16', teacher, "Apply reasoning about surface area and volume of prisms as well as proportional relationships to calculate how much material to build something will cost and explain the solution method.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U7-L16', student, "Let's explore things that are proportional to volume or surface area.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G7-U7-L16', "In this second lesson on applying surface area and volume to solve problems, students solve real-world problems of increased complexity that require them to choose which of the two quantities is appropriate for solving the problem, or whether both are appropriate for different aspects of the problem. They use previous work on ratios and proportional relationships, thus consolidating their knowledge and skill in that area. Students engage in aspects of mathematical modeling as they determine whether to use surface area or volume and consider how the constraints of the situation affect the solution.").
