vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G7-U8-L11', "Students often expect all relationships between quantities derived from the same geometric object to be proportional. This lesson reveals a critical limitation: while both perimeter and area increase with side length, the area grows quadratically (as the square of perimeter/4) and therefore fails the proportionality test—the line does not pass through the origin. Recognizing this requires students to distinguish between algebraic structure (which quantities relate linearly?) and geometric intuition.").

vision_lesson('IM-G7-U8-L12', 7, 8, 12, "Larger Populations").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U8-L12', teacher, "I can explain why it may be useful to gather data on a sample of a population.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U8-L12', teacher, "When I read or hear a statistical question, I can name the population of interest and give an example of a sample for that population.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U8-L12', student, "Let's compare larger groups.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G7-U8-L12', "This lesson introduces the idea of using data from a sample of a population when it is impractical or impossible to gather data from every individual in the population under study. A population includes all the individuals related to a question, and a sample is a part of the population. Students consider how information from students in their class might apply to larger populations, then identify possible samples from populations given a statistical question. They must also make sense of a problem in which the population is too large to collect data from and use samples to solve it.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G7-U8-L12', addressing, '7.SP.A.1').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G7-U8-L12', addressing, '7.SP.B').
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G7-U8-L12', "count_letters_in_names", "Varies by student; example: preferred name 5 letters, last name 8 letters", 'Activity 12.1, Student Task Statement (q', "195", text).
