vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G7-U8-L12', "This lesson is fundamentally about developing vocabulary and understanding why samples are useful, not about computing statistics. The core misconception students have is assuming that data from a small sample will always match the whole population exactly, or conversely, dismissing a sample because it looks different. Students often struggle to distinguish between a representative sample and a biased one. The lesson uses mean and MAD calculations as tools to make comparisons, but these are secondary to the primary goal of reasoning about populations and samples. Students at this level may con").

vision_lesson('IM-G7-U8-L13', 7, 8, 13, "Section C: Sampling").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U8-L13', teacher, "Describe methods to obtain a random sample from a population, and explain why it is representative of the population.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U8-L13', teacher, "Explain why samples are necessary and describe a sample and population for a given statistical question.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G7-U8-L13', "In this section, students examine samples taken from a larger population and use randomness to select a sample that is less biased than other methods. They begin by comparing two small populations based on their measures of center and variability. Then students consider much larger populations to motivate the need to sample to obtain data. This leads to considering how some samples may be more representative of the population than others and the idea that random selection is more likely to produce representative samples.").
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G7-U8-L13', "This lesson introduces sampling as a foundational statistical idea. Students move from comparing two complete small populations (gymnastics and volleyball team heights shown in dot plots) to understanding why sampling becomes necessary for large populations. The critical misconception is that convenience samples (like asking friends) represent populations well; the key learning is that random selection reduces bias and produces more representative samples. The lesson is conceptual rather than computational—students explain why sampling matters and discuss methods, not calculate numerical summa").

vision_lesson('IM-G7-U8-L14', 7, 8, 14, "Estimating Probabilities through Repeated Experiments").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U8-L14', teacher, "Describe (orally and in writing) patterns observed on a table or graph that show the relative frequency for a repeated experiment.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U8-L14', teacher, "Generalize (orally) that the cumulative relative frequency approaches the probability of the event as an experiment is repeated many times.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U8-L14', teacher, "Generate possible results that would or would not be surprising for a repeated experiment, and justify (orally) the reasoning.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G7-U8-L14', "In this lesson students roll a number cube many times and calculate the cumulative fraction of the trials for which an event occurs to see that in the long run this relative frequency approaches the probability of the event. Students must examine the structure of the repeated trials to recognize the connection between long-run frequency and probability (MP8). They also see that the relative frequency of a chance event will not usually exactly match the actual probability.").
