vision_lesson('IM-G7-U8-L18', 7, 8, 18, "Comparing Populations Using Samples").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U8-L18', teacher, "Calculate the difference between the mean or median of two samples from different populations, and express it as a multiple of the MAD or IQR.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U8-L18', teacher, "Interpret a pair of box plots, including the amount of visual overlap between the two distributions.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U8-L18', teacher, "Justify (orally and in writing) whether there is likely to be a meaningful difference between two populations based on a sample from each population.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U8-L18', student, "Let's compare different populations using samples.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G7-U8-L18', "In this lesson, students compare two groups based on samples from each group, building on earlier activities where they compared populations using measures of center and variability. Students learn that a small difference between sample measures of center, relative to their variability, does not mean the populations are meaningfully different, but a large difference—relative to variability—suggests the populations likely differ. The lesson establishes a decision rule: if sample measures of center are at least 2 MADs (or 2 IQRs) apart, there is likely a meaningful difference between the populations.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G7-U8-L18', building_on, '6.SP.B.5.c').
