vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G7-U8-L18', "This lesson establishes a quantitative decision rule for comparing populations via samples: the difference in means (or medians) must be at least 2 MADs (or 2 IQRs) apart to conclude a meaningful difference likely exists. Students often fail to account for sampling variability and may think any difference is meaningful, or they misinterpret visual overlap in dot plots and box plots as contradicting a real difference between populations.").

vision_lesson('IM-G7-U8-L19', 7, 8, 19, "Comparing Populations with Friends").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U8-L19', teacher, "Coordinate (orally) visual displays of data with descriptions of shape, measures of center, and measures of spread.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U8-L19', teacher, "Determine what information is needed to solve problems about using samples to compare populations. Ask questions to elicit that information.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U8-L19', teacher, "Explain (orally and in writing) whether two populations are likely to be meaningfully different using center and spread.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U8-L19', student, "Let's ask important questions to compare groups.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G7-U8-L19', "Students continue to practice comparing populations by using samples from each population. Outside the classroom, people who wish to compare groups will not typically have all of the useful statistics presented to them in a nice package, so they must determine what information to gather, then work through the comparison process. In this lesson, students are paired so that one student is presented with a situation and question while the other student has information to help answer the question. By this part of the unit, students should be more precise in their language about statistics involving samples and populations.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G7-U8-L19', building_on, '6.SP.B.4').
