vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G7-U8-L19', "This lesson teaches a critical judgment in statistics: when a difference between population samples is large enough to matter. Students learn to use the informal rule \"2 × spread\" (either 2 IQRs or 2 MADs) as a heuristic for meaningful difference. The key mistake is treating differences in raw numbers as automatic evidence of real population difference without accounting for variability. Students often neglect to check spread or fail to recognize that a difference of, say, 3 units might be negligible if the data varies by 10 units within each group.").

vision_lesson('IM-G7-U8-L20', 7, 8, 20, "Memory Test").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U8-L20', teacher, "Describe (orally) connections between sampling and probability").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U8-L20', teacher, "Generate a random sample and use it to make inferences (in writing) about the population").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U8-L20', teacher, "Justify (orally and in writing) whether a given method produces a random sample").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U8-L20', student, "Let's put it all together.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G7-U8-L20', "This lesson is optional. It gives students a chance to use the material they have learned in the unit with the final goal of comparing two populations, but it may be shortened or skipped due to time constraints. In this lesson, students apply what they have learned about probability, sampling, and comparing populations to analyze two data sets. Half of the class works with one data set while the other half of the class works with another. Students choose their own tools for selecting a sample at random (MP5) and calculate the mean, MAD, and a proportion to summarize their sample (MP2). Then students compare their results with a partner that had the other data set to construct an argument for whether there is a meaningful difference between the sets (MP3).").
