vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G7-U9-L2', "This lesson hinges on distinguishing proportional relationships (y = kx, passing through the origin) from linear but non-proportional relationships (y = mx + b with b ≠ 0). Students must interpret the y-intercept as a fixed/startup cost and the slope as a per-unit variable cost, then use these meanings to make economic decisions. A common misconception is that all linear equations represent proportional relationships. The lesson also demands careful unit coordination (mixing per-meal, per-day, and per-year costs) and interpretation of equation solutions in context—interpreting 671.6 days as 'a").

