vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G7-U9-L7', "Students frequently assume percent errors behave additively or multiplicatively like the quantities themselves: that two 5% errors in added measurements yield 10% error (not 5%), or in multiplied measurements yield 25% error (not 10.25%). The critical insight is that maximum percent errors occur when actual measurements fall below measured values. Measurement precision becomes a larger percentage of smaller quantities—a 1mm tolerance is 2% of a 5cm measurement but 0.6% of a 17.7cm measurement.").

vision_lesson('IM-G7-U9-L8', 7, 9, 8, "Deforestation at Scale").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U9-L8', teacher, "Calculate the area of forested land from a map.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U9-L8', teacher, "Describe the result of deforestation and reforestation on a model of development.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U9-L8', teacher, "Make simplifying assumptions to solve problems about estimating quantities.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U9-L8', student, "Let's compare the forested area over time.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G7-U9-L8', "In this optional lesson, students use maps to compare the forested area of a location at two different times. They begin by remembering strategies to calculate the area of a polygon. They then are presented with two maps of the same location, before and after development. Students compare the forested areas in each map and discuss the deforestation and reforestation in the area. Students make sense of the problem by making a plan for how to find the area of the forested land (MP1). They construct and critique arguments when comparing plans and solutions (MP3). This lesson relies on skills developed in Unit 1 but can be approached in more ways if taught after later units.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G7-U9-L8', addressing, '7.G.A.1').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G7-U9-L8', addressing, '7.G.B.6').
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G7-U9-L8', "scale_drawing_area_calculation", "256 square feet", 'After figure diagram showing room shape ', "62", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G7-U9-L8', "area_forested_map_before_development", "about 6,250,000 square feet", 'Question 1, Activity 8.3 Student Task St', "64", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G7-U9-L8', "area_forested_map_after_development", "about 3,355,000 square feet", 'Question 2, Activity 8.3 Student Task St', "64", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G7-U9-L8', "deforestation_magnitude_from_area_difference", "About 2,895,000 square feet of forested land was removed", 'Question 3, Activity 8.3 Student Task St', "64-65", text).
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G7-U9-L8', "Students must correctly scale areas from drawings (applying the square of the linear scale factor, not just the linear factor) and decompose irregular map regions into simpler polygons. The major challenge is accepting that different decomposition methods yield similar but slightly different answers—all potentially reasonable—while maintaining spatial reasoning about what regions qualify as forested land on an actual map.").

vision_lesson('IM-G7-U9-L9', 7, 9, 9, "Measuring Long Distances over Uneven Terrain").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U9-L9', teacher, "Choose a method and appropriate measuring tools to measure the length of a path.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U9-L9', teacher, "Compare and contrast (orally and in writing) methods for measuring long distances.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U9-L9', teacher, "Compare measurements of a path and represent (in writing) the difference between measurements as a percentage.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U9-L9', student, "Let's measure long distances over uneven terrain.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G7-U9-L9', "In this optional lesson, students brainstorm ideas about how to measure long distances, possibly over uneven terrain. As students work in groups to try out the accuracy and effectiveness of different methods, they construct arguments and critique the reasoning of others (MP3). Some of the methods involve proportional reasoning. Students use appropriate tools when they plan and try out methods of measurement (MP5).").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G7-U9-L9', building_on, '2.MD.A.1').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G7-U9-L9', addressing, '7.RP.A').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G7-U9-L9', building_toward, '7.RP.A').
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G7-U9-L9', "measure_path_length", "Answers vary; path length 50–100 meters", 'Activity 9.3, Question 1', "70-71", text).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G7-U9-L9', "percentage_difference_calculation", "2%", 'Activity 9.3, Question 3', "71", text).
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G7-U9-L9', "The lesson explores measurement methods that trade precision for feasibility: tape measures are accurate but cumbersome; stride-counting is fast but vulnerable to variation in individual gait and terrain. Students commonly underestimate how small errors in technique (uneven stride length, imprecise path-following) accumulate dramatically over longer distances.").

vision_lesson('IM-G7-U9-L10', 7, 9, 10, "Building a Trundle Wheel").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U9-L10', teacher, "Create a trundle wheel and use it to calculate the length of the classroom.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U9-L10', teacher, "Explain (orally and in writing) how a trundle wheel is used to measure long distances.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U9-L10', student, "Let's build a trundle wheel.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G7-U9-L10', "In this optional lesson, students build a trundle wheel, a device used to measure walking distances. First, they learn about a trundle wheel and discuss how such a device works and when it is the appropriate measuring tool. Then students use paper plates to make a usable trundle wheel and practice using it to measure distances in the classroom. Students can either use same-sized or different-sized paper plates to explore how diameter and circumference affect the precision of distance measurement.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G7-U9-L10', building_on, '7.G.B.4').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G7-U9-L10', addressing, '7.G.B.4').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G7-U9-L10', addressing, '7.RP.A').
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G7-U9-L10', "measure_plate_diameter", "26 cm", 'Activity 10.2, Student Response sample', "76-77", text).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G7-U9-L10', "calculate_circumference_from_diameter", "26π cm or about 81.7 cm", 'Activity 10.2, Student Response sample', "76-77", text).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G7-U9-L10', "count_wheel_rotations_across_distance", "12 clicks", 'Activity 10.2, Student Response sample', "76-77", text).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G7-U9-L10', "calculate_distance_from_rotations_and_circumference", "About 9.8 m (980.4 cm)", 'Activity 10.2, Student Response sample', "76-77", text).
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G7-U9-L10', "This lesson applies circle geometry (circumference = π × diameter) to practical measurement and requires understanding that circumference determines distance traveled per rotation. Students commonly misunderstand that smaller wheels produce more rotations for the same distance, or they miscalculate by failing to use the circumference scaling relationship to correct for wheel-size differences across groups.").

vision_lesson('IM-G7-U9-L11', 7, 9, 11, "Using a Trundle Wheel to Measure Distances").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U9-L11', teacher, "Calculate the distance of a path using the circumference and number of rotations of a trundle wheel.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U9-L11', teacher, "Compare measurement calculations and express differences between measurements as a percentage.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U9-L11', teacher, "Critique (orally) methods for measuring a long distance.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U9-L11', student, "Let's use our trundle wheels.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G7-U9-L11', "In this optional lesson, students use their trundle wheels to re-measure the distance they measured previously. By returning to the earlier problem with new tools, students make sense of and persevere in solving the problem (MP1). After students have had experience using their trundle wheels, they can connect their observations of how the wheel works with the distance computations and discuss the sources of errors in a more meaningful way. Students compare their previous measurements with their new measurements using the trundle wheel. This comparison allows them to refine their model by reconciling how to report the different measurements from each way of measuring (MP4).").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G7-U9-L11', addressing, '7.G.B.4').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G7-U9-L11', addressing, '7.RP.A').
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G7-U9-L11', "calculate_distance_from_wheel_rotations", "25π × 63 = 4,945.5 cm ≈ 49.5 m", 'Activity 1.1, Student Task Statement que', "79–80", text).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G7-U9-L11', "choose_reported_measurement", "50 m", 'Activity 1.1, question 2; Student Respon', "80", text).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G7-U9-L11', "express_percentage_difference", "2% (51 ÷ 50 = 1.02)", 'Activity 1.1, question 4; Student Respon', "80", text).
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G7-U9-L11', "This lesson connects physical measurement (rolling a wheel and counting rotations) to distance calculation using the formula distance = circumference × rotations. The main challenge is managing measurement variability: students take three measurements and get three different results, forcing a decision about what distance to report. Students often lose track of rotation counts during long-distance measurement and struggle to understand why repeated measurements differ. The lesson treats reporting precision realistically—to the nearest meter rather than centimeter, appropriate given the tool's").

vision_lesson('IM-G7-U9-L12', 7, 9, 12, "Designing a 5K Course").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U9-L12', teacher, "Calculate the distance of a path using the circumference and number of rotations of a trundle wheel.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U9-L12', teacher, "Create a scale drawing of a 5K course and present (using words and other representations) the map and course details.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G7-U9-L12', teacher, "Use proportional reasoning to calculate the number of laps of a course that is equal to 5 kilometers.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G7-U9-L12', "Student-facing goal: Let's map out the 5K course.  Lesson purpose: In this optional lesson, students design a 5K course and use their trundle wheels to measure distances. They draw a scale drawing of the course on a map or a satellite image of the school grounds, give instructions where the start and finish of the course should be, and decide how many laps are necessary to complete the race. Students use their experience with the smaller path to design a path of the required length (MP7). After planning their course, students use their trundle wheels to measure the course they planned and adjust their plan as necessary. As students measure their course, they decide the appropriate level of precision based on the tools they are using (MP6). This lesson may take 2 days.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G7-U9-L12', addressing, '7.G.A.1').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G7-U9-L12', addressing, '7.RP.A').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G7-U9-L12', addressing, '7.RP.A.3').
