vision_lesson_computation('IM-G7-U9-L12', "calculate_laps_from_estimated_distance", "10", 'Activity 1, Task 3', "83", text).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G7-U9-L12', "measure_actual_lap_distance_with_trundle_wheel", "625 meters", 'Activity 2, Task 1', "85", text).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G7-U9-L12', "calculate_laps_from_actual_measured_distance", "8", 'Activity 2, Task 3', "85", text).
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G7-U9-L12', "The lesson's core reasoning demand is the inverse relationship between lap length and the number of laps needed to walk 5 km; students must recalculate laps when measured distances differ from estimates, and many confuse the direction of change (longer laps = fewer laps).").

vision_lesson('IM-G8-U1-L1', 8, 1, 1, "Moving in the Plane").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U1-L1', teacher, "Describe (orally and in writing) a rotation of a shape using informal language, e.g., 'turn left,' 'quarter turn,' etc.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U1-L1', teacher, "Describe (orally and in writing) a translation of a shape using informal language, e.g., 'slide,' 'move,' 'shift,' etc.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U1-L1', student, "Let's describe ways figures can move in the plane.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G8-U1-L1', "The purpose of this lesson is to introduce students to translations and rotations of plane figures and to have them describe these movements in everyday language. Expect students to use words like 'slide' and 'turn.' In the next lesson, they will be introduced to the mathematical terms. The term 'transformation' is not yet used and will be introduced later in a later lesson.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U1-L1', building_on, '4.MD.C.5').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U1-L1', building_toward, '8.G.A.1').
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U1-L1', "identify_rotation_between_frames", "Turn counterclockwise 90 degrees", 'Cool-down Activity 1.3, Frame to Frame', "71", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U1-L1', "identify_rotation_across_positions", "The shape rotates 180 degrees", 'Practice Problem 2, Solution', "75", figure).
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G8-U1-L1', "This lesson introduces translations and rotations through informal description before formal terminology arrives. Students commonly confuse perspective—whether describing from an observer's viewpoint or the shape's own orientation—and struggle to express rotation direction (clockwise/counterclockwise) and amount (degrees) with consistency. The lesson depends entirely on informal language and visual pattern work; there is no formal coordinate system or algebraic work yet.").

vision_lesson('IM-G8-U1-L2', 8, 1, 2, "Naming the Moves").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U1-L2', teacher, "Describe (orally and in writing) the movement of shapes informally and formally using the terms 'clockwise,' 'counterclockwise,' 'translations,' 'rotations,' and 'reflections' of figures.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U1-L2', teacher, "Identify corresponding points before and after a transformation.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U1-L2', teacher, "Know the difference between translations, rotations, and reflections.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G8-U1-L2', "In this lesson, students are introduced to the terms translation, rotation, and reflection and begin to describe these transformations with greater precision. Students are also introduced to the terms clockwise and counterclockwise. Students then use this language to identify the individual moves on various figures. Students engage in mathematical practice 6 (precision) as they experiment with ways to describe moves precisely enough for another to understand their meaning.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U1-L2', building_on, '4.MD.C.5').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U1-L2', addressing, '8.G.A.1').
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G8-U1-L2', "This is a vocabulary and classification lesson, not computationally focused. Students learn to identify and describe three rigid transformations (translation, rotation, reflection) through visual observation and precise language. The major misconception: students often confuse reflections with rotations when figures are not on the same frame, or when they measure the acute angle between shapes instead of tracing to verify corresponding point mappings. Tracing paper is essential for differentiating these moves, especially distinguishing a reflection from a 180° rotation.").

vision_lesson('IM-G8-U1-L3', 8, 1, 3, "Grid Moves").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U1-L3', teacher, "Describe (orally) the moves needed to perform a translation, rotation, or reflection.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U1-L3', teacher, "Draw and label the image of figures that result from translations, rotations, and reflections on a square or isometric grid.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U1-L3', student, "Let's transform some figures on grids.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G8-U1-L3', "Students build on prior knowledge of translations, rotations, and reflections by applying these moves to figures on both square grids and isometric grids. They label transformed points using prime notation (P → P') and develop flexibility in performing rigid transformations using tracing paper or grid-based reasoning. The isometric grid (composed of equilateral triangles meeting at vertices) introduces a new structure where transformations work differently from square grids, particularly for rotations at 60-degree increments. GeoGebra provides a digital transformation tool for classrooms using the digital curriculum.\"").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U1-L3', building_on, '7.G.A').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U1-L3', addressing, '8.G.A.1').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U1-L3', building_toward, '8.G.A.1').
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G8-U1-L3', "This lesson is purely geometric construction, not numerical computation. Students draw and describe transformations but don't solve equations or measure quantities. Common misunderstandings: students struggle to visualize reflections over non-horizontal/non-vertical lines, confuse rotation direction, and are often surprised that no 90-degree angles exist on the isometric grid (only 60-degree multiples). Tracing paper is essential for students who lack strong spatial visualization.").

vision_lesson('IM-G8-U1-L4', 8, 1, 4, "Making the Moves").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U1-L4', teacher, "Draw a transformation of a figure using information given orally.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U1-L4', teacher, "Explain (orally) the sequence of transformations that takes one figure to its image.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U1-L4', teacher, "Identify (orally and in writing) the features that determine a translation, rotation, or reflection.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U1-L4', student, "Let's draw and describe translations, rotations, and reflections.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G8-U1-L4', "In the previous lesson, students were introduced to the terms \"translation,\" \"rotation,\" and \"reflection.\" In this lesson, students understand that a translation is determined by two points that specify the distance and direction of the translation; a rotation is determined by a point, angle of rotation, and a direction of rotation; and a reflection is determined by a line. These moves are called \"transformations\" for the first time, and students draw images of figures under these transformations and study sequences of these transformations that take one figure to another. A subtle language shift occurs: in the previous lesson, one shape \"moves\" to the other as if the original shape has agency; now the transformation \"takes\" one shape to the other, centering the transformation itself as the object of study. Students using print may use tracing paper; digital students have access to applets to perform transformations. Students are likely starting to think strategically about which transformations will take one figure to another, identifying properties of the shapes that indicate whether a translation, rotation, reflection, or sequence of these will achieve this goal (MP7).").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U1-L4', addressing, '8.G.A.1').
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G8-U1-L4', "This lesson develops students' ability to precisely describe the three rigid transformations (translation, rotation, reflection) and to identify them visually. A major challenge is that incomplete descriptions are common: students forget to specify distance and direction for translations, or the direction (clockwise/counterclockwise) for rotations, or which line for reflections. Students also need to see that multiple transformation sequences can produce the same image, requiring strategic thinking about which combination most efficiently maps one figure to another.").

vision_lesson('IM-G8-U1-L5', 8, 1, 5, "Coordinate Moves (Grade 8, Unit 1, Lesson 5)").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U1-L5', teacher, "Determine (orally and in writing) coordinates that represent the image of a polygon in the coordinate plane after a transformation").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U1-L5', teacher, "Draw and label a diagram of a line segment rotated 90 degrees clockwise or counterclockwise about a given center").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U1-L5', teacher, "Generalize (orally and in writing) the process to reflect any point in the coordinate plane over the x-axis or y-axis").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U1-L5', student, "Let's transform some figures and see what happens to the coordinates of points.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G8-U1-L5', "Students use coordinates to describe figures and their images under transformations. Reflections over the x-axis and y-axis have structure captured by coordinates: reflecting (2, 5) over the x-axis yields (2, -5) because distance from the axis stays the same but position reverses. Coordinate structure helps visualize how transformations affect points, introducing MP7 (discovering patterns coordinates obey).").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U1-L5', building_on, '8.G.A.1').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U1-L5', addressing, '8.G.A.3').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U1-L5', building_toward, '8.G.A.3').
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U1-L5', "reflect_point_over_x_axis", "(13, 10) → (13, -10); (13, -20) → (13, 20); (13, 570) → (13, -570)", 'Activity 5.2, Student Task, Question 2', "127–128", text).
