vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G8-U1-L8', "The lesson centers on the three outcomes of 180-degree rotation depending on the center: parallel segments (center not on segment), collinear segments (center on or at endpoint), or identical segments with endpoints switched (center at midpoint). Students commonly believe rotating around the midpoint will move the segment; the key insight is that the segment stays in place while endpoints trade positions. Understanding these properties is essential for later work with composite figures and the Pythagorean theorem.").

vision_lesson('IM-G8-U1-L9', 8, 1, 9, "Moves in Parallel").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U1-L9', teacher, "Draw and label rigid transformations of lines and parallel lines and explain (orally and in writing) the relationship between the original and its image under the transformation.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U1-L9', teacher, "Generalize that a rotation by 180 degrees about a point of two intersecting lines moves each angle to the angle that is vertical to it.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U1-L9', teacher, "Justify (orally) that vertical angles are congruent using informal arguments about 180-degree rotations of lines.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U1-L9', student, "Let's transform some lines.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G8-U1-L9', "The focus of this lesson is for students to observe the effects of rigid transformations on lines and parallel lines. Parallel lines do not meet and are the same distance apart along their entire length, and a rigid transformation does not change these features. Students use the structure of parallel lines to conclude that the image of a set of parallel lines is also a set of parallel lines under a rigid transformation. Students also investigate 180-degree rotations of points on a line and a set of intersecting lines, using arguments about 180-degree rotations to justify that vertical angles have the same measure.").
