vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G8-U1-L10', "This lesson asks students to apply rigid transformations to build composite figures and use properties of these transformations to find unknown side lengths and angle measures without direct measurement. The central challenge is that students often struggle to identify which angles and segments correspond between an original figure and its transformed images, and they may not yet trust that a 180° rotation guarantees parallelism of opposite sides—reasoning that requires understanding that rotation preserves distance and angle, which makes corresponding sides parallel.").

vision_lesson('IM-G8-U1-L11', 8, 1, 11, "What Is the Same?").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U1-L11', teacher, "Compare and contrast (orally and in writing) side lengths, angle measures, and other features of shapes using rigid transformations to explain why a shape is or is not congruent to another").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U1-L11', teacher, "Describe (orally and in writing) two figures that can be moved to one another using a rigid transformation as congruent").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U1-L11', teacher, "Explain that congruent figures have equal corresponding side lengths, angle measures, and areas").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U1-L11', student, "Let's decide whether shapes are the same.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G8-U1-L11', "Students explore what it means for shapes to be \"the same\" by examining mirror images, comparing pairs of figures to construct arguments about sameness, learning that two figures are congruent if a sequence of translations, rotations, and reflections moves one to the other, and investigating how area and perimeter relate to congruence using tools like rulers, protractors, and tracing paper.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U1-L11', addressing, '8.G.A.1').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U1-L11', addressing, '8.G.A.2').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U1-L11', building_toward, '8.G.A.2').
