vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G8-U1-L15', "Students discover empirically that all triangles have interior angles summing to exactly 180° by cutting angles, matching congruent triangles, and testing angle combinations. The core misconception is that students believe any three positive angles can form a triangle, or that the property applies only to special cases (equilateral, isosceles) rather than universally.").

vision_lesson('IM-G8-U1-L16', 8, 1, 16, "Parallel Lines and the Angles in a Triangle").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U1-L16', teacher, "Create diagrams using 180-degree rotations of triangles to justify (orally and in writing) that the measure of angles in a triangle sum up to 180 degrees.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U1-L16', teacher, "Generalize that the sum of angles in a triangle is 180 degrees using rigid transformations or the congruence of alternate interior angles of parallel lines cut by a transversal.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U1-L16', student, "Let's see why the angles in a triangle add to 180 degrees.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G8-U1-L16', "In this lesson, students apply properties of rigid transformations to show that the sum of the interior angles of any triangle is 180°. Students first use rigid transformations to explore the sum of angles in a triangle drawn on a grid by rotating the triangle so that angles corresponding to its three interior angles form a straight line, demonstrating the sum equals 180°. However, this argument depends on grid lines to show the three angles form a straight angle. Students then complete the argument without using a grid by using the structure of parallel lines cut by a transversal, corresponding parts of congruent triangles, and straight angles to generalize that the sum of angles in any triangle is 180°. An optional activity provides additional practice using the same structure to find angle measures in composite figures.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U1-L16', building_on, '7.NS.A').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U1-L16', building_on, '8.G.A.1.b').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U1-L16', addressing, '8.G.A.5').
