vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G8-U2-L5', "This lesson centers on how coordinates enable precise communication in dilations. Students must identify and provide three pieces of information—vertices' coordinates, the center of dilation, and the scale factor—to fully describe a dilation. Common obstacles: students may omit one of these pieces, struggle with fractional (less than 1) scale factors, or fail to recognize that the coordinate grid makes the center's location unambiguous without pictures.").

vision_lesson('IM-G8-U2-L6', 8, 2, 6, "Similarity").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U2-L6', teacher, "Comprehend that the phrase 'similar figures' (in written and spoken language) means there is a sequence of translations, rotations, reflections, and dilations that takes one figure to the other.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U2-L6', teacher, "Justify (orally) the similarity of two figures using a sequence of transformations that takes one figure to the other.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G8-U2-L6', "The purpose of this lesson is to define that two figures are similar if there is a sequence of translations, rotations, reflections, and dilations that takes one figure to the other. It is important to note that there are many different sequences that could show two figures are similar.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U2-L6', building_on, '8.G.A.2').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U2-L6', addressing, '8.G.A.2').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U2-L6', addressing, '8.G.A.4').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U2-L6', building_toward, '8.G.A.4').
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G8-U2-L6', "This lesson defines similarity through transformation sequences (translations, rotations, reflections, dilations) rather than through computation or measurement. Students do not solve equations or compute quantities; they identify, describe, sketch, and justify transformation sequences. Common misconceptions: students believe only one sequence of transformations works (in fact many do); they struggle to identify the correct center of dilation or the correct order of transformations; they may not recognize that scale factors less than 1 represent shrinking. The reasoning required is spatial and").

vision_lesson('IM-G8-U2-L7', 8, 2, 7, "Similar Polygons").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U2-L7', teacher, "Comprehend the phrase 'similar polygons' (in written and spoken language) to mean the polygons have congruent corresponding angles and proportional side lengths.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U2-L7', teacher, "Critique (orally) arguments that claim two polygons are similar.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U2-L7', teacher, "I can use angle measures and side lengths to conclude that two polygons are not similar.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U2-L7', teacher, "I know the relationship between angle measures and side lengths in similar polygons.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U2-L7', student, "Let's look at sides and angles of similar polygons.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G8-U2-L7', "The focus of this lesson is on quadrilaterals and ways to decide whether or not they are similar. Since the transformations we have studied (translations, rotations, reflections, dilations) do not change angle measures, similar polygons will have congruent corresponding angles. Also, since dilations scale all side lengths by the same scale factor, similar polygons will have proportional corresponding side lengths. While these two key ideas can determine whether two polygons are not similar, using them to determine that polygons are similar will not be formally proven until high school. In grade 8, similar figures are identified using transformations.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U2-L7', addressing, '8.G.A.2').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U2-L7', addressing, '8.G.A.4').
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U2-L7', "find_similar_triangle_sides", "a = 7, b = 15", 'Practice Problems, Problem 4', "146-147", figure).
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G8-U2-L7', "Similar figures require both congruent corresponding angles AND the same scale factor applied to all side lengths. Students frequently confuse sufficiency of either property alone: thinking equal side lengths guarantee similarity (ignoring angles), or that equal angles guarantee similarity (ignoring proportional sides). This lesson emphasizes that both conditions are necessary, introducing a criterion that goes beyond single-property checks.").

vision_lesson('IM-G8-U2-L8', 8, 2, 8, "Constructing a Square with Rotations and Translations").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U2-L8', student, "Draw a horizontal line segment, rotate it to form perpendicular sides at two corners, and describe the final transformation needed to complete a square.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G8-U2-L8', "This practice problem consolidates understanding of how rigid transformations (rotation and translation) work together to construct geometric figures with specific properties (equal sides, right angles, parallel opposite sides).").
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U2-L8', "rigid_shape_composition", "A horizontal line segment AB of student-chosen length", 'part a', "148", text).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U2-L8', "rotation_90_counterclockwise", "A new segment attached at point A, perpendicular to AB (forming a right angle)", 'part b', "148", text).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U2-L8', "rotation_90_clockwise", "A new segment attached at point B, perpendicular to AB, parallel and in same direction as the segment from part b", 'part c', "148", text).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U2-L8', "identify_final_transformation", "Translate the original segment AB to position C (the new point from part b)", 'part d', "148", text).
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G8-U2-L8', "This lesson teaches how rigid transformations compose to build figures. Students commonly struggle with rotation-center dependence (why rotating around A vs. B gives different results) and visualizing the completed square without drawing it. The critical insight is that the two rotations create two perpendicular sides meeting at right angles, and translation of the original segment completes the square—so the same segment length repeats and opposite sides stay parallel.").

vision_lesson('IM-G8-U2-L9', 8, 2, 9, "Side Length Quotients in Similar Triangles").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U2-L9', teacher, "Calculate unknown side lengths in similar triangles using the ratios of side lengths within the triangles and the scale factor between similar triangles.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U2-L9', teacher, "Generalize (orally) that the quotients of pairs of side lengths in similar triangles are equal.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U2-L9', student, "Let's find missing side lengths in triangles.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G8-U2-L9', "The purpose of this lesson is for students to see that the quotient of a pair of side lengths in one triangle will always be equal to the quotient of the corresponding side lengths in a similar triangle. While this fact is not limited to triangles, this lesson focuses on the particular case of triangles so that students are ready to investigate the concept of slope in upcoming lessons. The lesson begins with students determining if two triangles are similar given only their side lengths and no drawing, prompting them to attempt finding a common scale factor between corresponding sides. Next, students calculate the quotients of pairs of side lengths in similar triangles and find that the quotients for corresponding pairs of sides are the same. Finally, students use this information to calculate missing side lengths in a set of three similar triangles.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U2-L9', building_on, '7.RP.A.2').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U2-L9', addressing, '8.G.A').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U2-L9', addressing, '8.G.A.4').
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U2-L9', "multiply_side_by_scale_factor", "8", 'Activity 9.2, part 1', "168-169", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U2-L9', "compute_quotient_of_corresponding_sides", "1.75 or 7/4", 'Activity 9.2, part 2', "169", text).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U2-L9', "find_missing_side_from_quotient", "d = 10", 'Activity 9.3', "172", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U2-L9', "find_missing_sides_using_scale_factor", "a = 6, b = 22.5", 'Practice Problem 1', "176", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U2-L9', "compute_side_quotient_and_compare_across_similar_triangles", "5/4 or 1.25 (same for both ABC and XYZ)", 'Practice Problem 2, part d', "176-177", text).
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G8-U2-L9', "The lesson's core insight is that quotients of corresponding side lengths are equal within similar triangles, which directly prepares students for slope. Students often conflate two strategies — using an external scale factor (multiplying/dividing by the ratio between triangles) versus using internal quotients (the ratio of two sides within one triangle) — and may not recognize when each method is most efficient. A second common misunderstanding: students may verify similarity by checking that one or two pairs of sides satisfy a scale factor without confirming that all corresponding sides obey").

vision_lesson('IM-G8-U2-L10', 8, 2, 10, "Meet Slope").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U2-L10', teacher, "Comprehend the term slope to mean a number that tells how steep a line is, found by dividing the vertical change by the horizontal change for any two points on the line.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U2-L10', teacher, "Draw a line on a grid given its slope and describe observations about lines with the same slope.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U2-L10', teacher, "Justify that all slope triangles on one line are similar.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U2-L10', student, "Let's learn about the slope of a line.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G8-U2-L10', "In this lesson, students use dilations and triangle similarity to understand why the slope of a line can be calculated by dividing the vertical change by the horizontal change for any two points on the line. Students also see that this ratio determines how steep the line is.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U2-L10', building_on, '8.G.A.4').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U2-L10', addressing, '8.EE.B.6').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U2-L10', building_toward, '8.EE.B.6').
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U2-L10', "slope_triangle_ratio_table", "Triangle ABC: 3/4 or 0.75; Triangle CDE: 6/8 or 0.75; Triangle FGH: 1.5/2 or 0.75", 'Activity 10.2, Question 2, table complet', "188", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U2-L10', "identify_line_slope_from_graph", "Line ℓ has a slope of 1; line k has a slope of 2", 'Activity 10.4, Question 1', "194-195", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U2-L10', "slope_quotient_similar_triangles", "Both triangles yield (vertical)÷(horizontal)=1/2; slope of line is 1/2", 'Practice Problem 3, parts c and d', "198", figure).
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G8-U2-L10', "Slope is a line property revealed through triangle similarity: all similar slope triangles on the same line produce an identical quotient when vertical change is divided by horizontal change. Students frequently misconceive that slope triangles must be congruent (identical size) rather than merely similar (same shape), or they confuse vertical versus horizontal measurement.").

vision_lesson('IM-G8-U2-L11', 8, 2, 11, "Writing Equations for Lines").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U2-L11', teacher, "Create an equation relating the quotient of the vertical and horizontal side lengths of a slope triangle to the slope of a line.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U2-L11', teacher, "Justify (orally) whether a point is on a line by finding quotients of horizontal and vertical distances.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U2-L11', student, "Let's explore the relationship between points on a line and the slope of the line.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G8-U2-L11', "The purpose of this lesson is for students to use the similarity relationship between slope triangles to write a relationship satisfied by any point on a non-vertical line. Students are shown a line on the coordinate plane that passes through (0, 0) and asked to determine if given points are on that line. Through repeated reasoning, students describe a rule that can test whether or not a point (x, y) is on the line. When students are shown a line that does not pass through (0, 0), the key idea to introduce is that a point with coordinates (x, y) represents a general point on the line. By noticing that all slope triangles lead to the same value of slope, this general point can be used to write a relationship satisfied by all points on the line.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U2-L11', building_on, '7.RP.A.2').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U2-L11', building_on, '8.G.A').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U2-L11', addressing, '8.EE.B.6').
