vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G8-U2-L11', "This lesson introduces the slope-quotient equation as a test for whether a point lies on a line: the key insight is that all points on a line (except the y-axis intercept if the line doesn't pass through the origin) satisfy the same ratio of rise over run. The most common student misunderstanding is failing to recognize that different-sized slope triangles on the same line produce equivalent ratios—they may think only one specific triangle or one specific calculation is valid. Students also often struggle with the notation (y−b)/(x−a) = m for lines not passing through the origin, and may forge").

