vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G8-U3-L4', "This lesson hinges on students' ability to extract and compare the rate of change from different representations—equations, tables, and graphs—to answer practical questions. The most common misunderstanding is reversing the variables in a rate (e.g., thinking 4 cups lemonade mix per cup water instead of 4 cups water per cup mix), confusing which quantity is numerator and denominator. Students benefit from explicitly connecting the rate value to the context and checking their interpretation against tables or graphs. No new arithmetic strategy is demanded; students apply familiar multiplication").

vision_lesson('IM-G8-U3-L5', 8, 3, 5, "Introduction to Linear Relationships").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U3-L5', teacher, "Compare and contrast (orally and in writing) proportional and nonproportional linear relationships.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U3-L5', teacher, "Interpret (orally and in writing) features of the graph (i.e., slope and y-intercept) of a non-proportional linear relationship.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U3-L5', student, "Let's explore some relationships between two variables.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G8-U3-L5', "In this lesson, students examine linear relationships with positive rates of change using a context where the height of a stack of styrofoam cups is not proportional to the number of cups. They observe that each cup increases the height by the same amount, making this a linear relationship with a constant rate of change. Using graphs, tables, and equations, students identify and describe similarities and differences between linear and proportional relationships, observing that the rate of change equals the slope of the line. The vertical intercept is introduced briefly but will be revisited in later lessons; the focus here is on rate of change in non-proportional linear relationships.").
