vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G8-U3-L5', "Students commonly conflate linearity with proportionality; this lesson explicitly separates them by showing how non-proportional relationships (with non-zero y-intercepts) can still be linear. A key misunderstanding: thinking that because a relationship has a starting value or doesn't pass through the origin, it isn't linear. The lesson teaches that the rate of change of a non-proportional linear relationship equals the slope of its graph, an insight that demands distinguishing the rate from the constant of proportionality.").

