vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G8-U4-L5', "This lesson demands students shift from solving simple, isolated equations to managing equations where variables appear on both sides. The central mathematical work is understanding that each solving step (add, subtract, multiply, divide by the same quantity on both sides) preserves the balance, not merely following a recipe. The most frequent error is careless application of the distributive property—students distribute a coefficient or factor to one term but forget others—and mishandling of negative numbers when multiplying or dividing both sides.").

vision_lesson('IM-G8-U4-L6', 8, 4, 6, "Strategic Solving").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U4-L6', teacher, "Categorize (orally and in writing) linear equations in one variable based on their structure, and solve equations from each category.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U4-L6', teacher, "Describe (orally and in writing) features of linear equations that have one solution, no solution, or many solutions.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U4-L6', teacher, "Describe (orally) strategies for solving linear equations in one variable with different features or structures.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U4-L6', student, "Let's solve linear equations like a boss.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G8-U4-L6', "In this lesson, students learn to think strategically before plunging into a solution method. After a Warm-up in which they construct their own equation to solve a problem, they look at equations with different structures and decide whether the solution will be positive, negative, or zero, without solving the equation. They judge which equations are likely to be easy for them to solve and which are likely to be difficult for them.").
