vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G8-U4-L6', "This lesson teaches students to examine equation structure—predicting whether solutions are positive, negative, or zero—before solving complex linear equations with fractions, distribution, and variables on both sides. Common misconception: students fear 'complicated-looking' equations rather than recognizing that structure-based simplification strategies (clearing fractions, collecting like terms) work most efficiently.").

vision_lesson('IM-G8-U4-L7', 8, 4, 7, "All, Some, or No Solutions").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U4-L7', teacher, "Compare and contrast (orally and in writing) equations that have no solutions or infinitely many solutions.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U4-L7', teacher, "Create linear equations in one variable that have either no solutions or infinitely many solutions, using structure, and explain (orally) the solution method.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U4-L7', teacher, "I can determine whether an equation has no solutions, one solution, or infinitely many solutions.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U4-L7', student, "Let's think about how many solutions an equation can have.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G8-U4-L7', "In this lesson, students encounter equations that have no solutions and equations for which every number is a solution. In the first case, when students try to solve the equation, they end up with a false statement like 0 = 5. In the second case, they end up with a statement that is always true, such as 6x = 6x. In preparation for predicting the number of solutions from the structure of an equation, students add missing terms in three different ways to make them have no solution, one solution, or infinitely many solutions.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U4-L7', addressing, '8.EE.C.7.a').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U4-L7', building_toward, '8.EE.C.7.a').
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G8-U4-L7', "This lesson operates entirely at the conceptual level—students learn to classify and predict solution types (no, one, or infinitely many) based on equation structure, without solving equations in the traditional sense. Common misconceptions: conflating \"always true\" with \"has one solution\" (e.g., thinking 2x = 2x means x has a single value rather than all values work), failing to simplify before classifying (e.g., not recognizing 2r + 6 = 2(r + 3) as an identity), and mistaking visual complexity for solution uniqueness. The breakthrough is linguistic and structural, not computational—students").

