vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U4-L15', teacher, "Distinguish between mathematical domain constraints and contextual constraints").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U4-L15', teacher, "Recognize when negative values are physically or definitionally impossible").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U4-L15', student, "Select all the situations for which only zero or positive solutions make sense.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G8-U4-L15', "Students evaluate contextual situations to determine which quantities are constrained to zero or positive values, deepening their understanding of when negative numbers are meaningful and when they are not.").
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U4-L15', "discriminate_nonnegative_from_negative_contexts", "B, D, F", 'Problem 5, Student Task Statement', "69", text).
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G8-U4-L15', "This lesson asks students to recognize that some real-world quantities are constrained to nonnegative values by definition or physical law, while others can meaningfully be negative depending on context and reference point. Common confusion: students often treat all quantities the same way, or fail to recognize that bank accounts can go negative (debt) and elevation can go below sea level. The correct answer (B: burning candle, D: student count, F: oven temperature on a hot day) passes only when students internalize that height, count, and certain temperature measurements have built-in nonnega").

