vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G8-U5-L9', "This lesson teaches model selection and the limits of linear approximation. Students must develop judgment about when a linear model is appropriate and over what domain it remains valid. The critical insight is that real-world phenomena (moon cycles, organism growth, resource trends) often follow nonlinear patterns—a model that fits one time interval may fail badly in another. Students commonly assume that any roughly linear-looking data can be modeled with a single line forever, rather than recognizing that models require domain restrictions and comparative evaluation. This requires reasoning").

