vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G8-U6-L2', "This lesson introduces scatter plots as the primary tool for investigating relationships between two paired quantitative variables. The critical shift is that each point represents two measurements about one object or person—students often initially misinterpret a scatter plot as two independent distributions. A secondary common confusion: students may think visible patterns (e.g., heavier books have more pages) imply a causal relationship. The lesson also emphasizes appropriate scaling and labeling of axes to avoid misleading impressions. No new arithmetic or algebraic operations are demanded").

vision_lesson('IM-G8-U6-L3', 8, 6, 3, "What a Point in a Scatter Plot Means").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U6-L3', teacher, "Coordinate (orally and in writing) data in a table and points on a scatter plot").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U6-L3', teacher, "Describe (orally) the trend of the data, and use the trend to predict unknown values").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U6-L3', teacher, "Interpret (orally and in writing) a point on a scatter plot in context").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U6-L3', student, "Let's investigate points in scatter plots.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G8-U6-L3', "In this lesson, students interpret points in a scatter plot in terms of a context and add points given information about individuals. They compare individuals represented by different points and informally discuss trends. The lesson develops two levels of analysis: what happens for a particular individual (zoom in on a point's coordinates) and what happens at the global level for the entire population (observe the overall pattern). Students spend significant time identifying quantities in a scatter plot and focusing on individual-point meaning.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U6-L3', building_on, '5.G.A.2').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U6-L3', addressing, '8.SP.A.1').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U6-L3', addressing, '8.SP.A.3').
