vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G8-U6-L5', "This lesson introduces positive and negative association through informal fitting of lines to scatter plots. The key misconception students often hold is that a good-fit line must either split points equally (half on each side) or pass through the outermost points. In reality, a good fit goes through the center of the data cloud and matches the overall trend; the lesson addresses this qualitatively through visual judgment and model comparison. Formal measures of fit (residuals, $R^2$) come in later grades.").

vision_lesson('IM-G8-U6-L6', 8, 6, 6, "The Slope of a Fitted Line").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U6-L6', teacher, "Interpret features of data on a scatter plot, including linear and non-linear association, outliers, slope of a linear model, and clustering.").
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U6-L6', "classify_scatter_plot_linearity", "non-linear association", 'Student Task Statement, part a', "83", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U6-L6', "identify_and_circle_clusters", "Two clusters present: x-values between 5 and 20, and x-values between 30 and 45", 'Student Task Statement, part b', "83", figure).
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G8-U6-L6', "This lesson assesses interpretation of scatter plots. Students must distinguish linear from non-linear patterns (recognizing that data can be scattered without following a trend) and visually identify clusters. The visible pages (83-84) show the assessment portion only; student-facing goal, lesson purpose, and CCSS standards are not included in this excerpt. Students commonly mistake variability in data for non-linearity, or they confuse isolated points with clusters; the lesson requires nuanced visual reasoning about overall pattern rather than computation.").

vision_lesson('IM-G8-U6-L7', 8, 6, 7, "Observing More Patterns in Scatter Plots").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U6-L7', teacher, "Categorize data sets, and describe (orally) the properties used to create categories.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U6-L7', teacher, "Describe (orally) features of data on scatter plots, including \"linear\" and \"non-linear association\" and \"clustering,\" using informal language.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U6-L7', teacher, "Explain (orally) what might cause a non-linear association or clustering of data points in context.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U6-L7', student, "Let's look for other patterns in data.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G8-U6-L7', "In this lesson, students see non-linear associations for the first time and use a Card Sort to distinguish linear and non-linear associations. They visually identify clusters in data and explain that this may be caused by subgroups within a data set exhibiting different trends. At this level, students rely on the structure of visual patterns in scatter plots (MP7) to recognize non-linear associations and clustering rather than quantitative tools.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U6-L7', addressing, '8.SP.A.1').
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G8-U6-L7', "This lesson introduces non-linear associations and clustering as visual phenomena—students recognize meaningful patterns through visual inspection alone, without slope calculations or statistical measures. Students commonly misinterpret curved data or scattered clusters as random noise rather than as patterns indicating subgroups or nonlinear relationships that warrant investigation into cause. The formalism here stays entirely informal: oral description and visual reasoning only.").

vision_lesson('IM-G8-U6-L8', 8, 6, 8, "The Slope of a Fitted Line").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U6-L8', teacher, "Describe (orally and in writing) the relationship between two variables using a line fit to data on a scatter plot.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U6-L8', teacher, "Interpret (orally and in writing) points on the scatter plot, including points that do and do not lie on a line fit to data.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U6-L8', teacher, "Interpret (orally and in writing) the slope of a line fit to data in context.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U6-L8', student, "Let's look at how changing one variable changes another.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G8-U6-L8', "In this lesson students focus on the mathematical language of slope using the context of data (MP6). Students also identify positive and negative associations of scatter plots without a fitted line shown (MP7).").
