vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G8-U6-L8', "This lesson bridges numerical and contextual reasoning about slope. Students must connect the abstract number (e.g., 0.85 or -0.011) to its lived meaning: for every 1-unit increase in the independent variable, the dependent variable changes by that amount. The core difficulty is not calculating slope—it is interpreting negative slopes correctly (a negative slope means both variables move in opposite directions, not that things are getting worse), reading slopes from graphs and equations accurately, and deciding when a linear model fits. Students often confuse scatter, trend, and fit; they reve").

vision_lesson('IM-G8-U6-L9', 8, 6, 9, "Looking for Associations").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U6-L9', teacher, "Calculate relative frequencies, and describe (orally and in writing) associations between variables using a relative frequency table.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U6-L9', teacher, "Coordinate (orally and in writing) two-way tables, bar graphs, and segmented bar graphs representing the same data.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U6-L9', student, "Let's look for associations in data.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G8-U6-L9', "In this lesson, students study categorical data displayed in two-way tables, bar graphs, and segmented bar graphs. A two-way table organizes categorical data based on two variables; a segmented bar graph visualizes the percentage of data within categories. Different graphical representations help students visualize frequencies and relative frequencies. Relative frequencies are percentages or fractions of the whole represented by a category. While the concepts are not very complex, there are many new terms and representations; students study them carefully so that they can make sense of them.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U6-L9', addressing, '8.SP.A.4').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U6-L9', building_toward, '8.SP.A.4').
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U6-L9', "complete_relative_frequency_table_row_percentages", "Row 1 (10-12 years): 42%, 58%; Row 2 (13-15 years): 80%, 20%; Row 3 (16-18 years): 83%, 17%", 'Activity 9.3 \'Building Another Type of T', "174-175", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U6-L9', "complete_relative_frequency_table_row_percentages_sports", "Row 1 (plays sport): 11%, 89%; Row 2 (does not play sport): 71%, 29%", 'Activity 9.4 \'Guitar and Golf\', Student ', "179-180", figure).
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G8-U6-L9', "The core insight is that relative frequencies reveal associations better than raw counts. Students commonly divide by the wrong denominator (the grand total instead of the row total), which masks the pattern; watch for this error. An association exists when proportions differ across groups, and relative frequency tables make these differences explicit and comparable.").

vision_lesson('IM-G8-U6-L10', 8, 6, 10, "Using Data Displays to Find Associations").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U6-L10', teacher, "Create a two-way table and a segmented bar graph that represent relative frequencies, and interpret (orally) the frequencies in context.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U6-L10', teacher, "Determine (in writing) whether categorical data has a positive, negative, or no association using a relative frequency table or segmented bar graph, and justify (orally) the reasoning.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G8-U6-L10', "In this lesson, students use two-way tables, bar graphs, and segmented bar graphs to decide whether or not there is evidence of an association in categorical data (MP4). At this level, students are looking for relative frequencies that appear very different between categories.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U6-L10', addressing, '8.SP.A.4').
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U6-L10', "complete_two_way_table", "11, 5, 4, 9, 10 (missing cell and row/column totals via subtraction from marginals)", 'Activity 10.1, Question 1', "186", figure).
