vision_lesson('IM-G8-U6-L17', 8, 6, 17, "Cylinder Volume as a Function of Height").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U6-L17', teacher, "Students write function equations for real-world contexts (cylinder volume)").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U6-L17', teacher, "Students sketch and interpret linear graphs").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U6-L17', teacher, "Students connect algebraic and graphical representations to reason about proportional relationships").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U6-L17', teacher, "Students verify scaling claims using equation substitution and graphical properties").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U6-L17', student, "Write an equation and sketch a graph to represent volume as a function of height for cylinders with fixed radius. Analyze how scaling the height affects the volume using both algebraic and graphical reasoning.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G8-U6-L17', "This lesson develops functional thinking and strengthens connections between symbolic and graphical reasoning. It uses cylinders (a familiar geometric object) to make concrete the abstract relationship between variables and to show that fixing one parameter (radius) while varying another (height) produces a linear function—a foundation for understanding function families.").
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U6-L17', "write_cylinder_volume_equation", "V = 36πh", 'part (a)', "67", text).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U6-L17', "evaluate_volume_at_height_1", "V ≈ 113 cubic meters", 'part (b), graph point', "67", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U6-L17', "evaluate_volume_at_height_2", "V ≈ 226 cubic meters", 'part (b), graph point', "67", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U6-L17', "height_doubling_volume_effect", "volume doubles", 'part (c)', "67", text).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U6-L17', "height_quarter_scaling_volume_effect", "volume is multiplied by 1/4", 'part (d)', "67", figure).
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G8-U6-L17', "This lesson hinges on understanding that when one parameter (radius) is fixed, volume becomes a linear function of height—meaning proportional scaling works uniformly. Students often struggle to see why volume must scale linearly with height, and may conflate this with area or volume scaling in non-linear contexts (where both dimensions change). The critical move is recognizing that the equation V = 36πh exposes the constant of proportionality (36π), making scaling claims checkable both algebraically and graphically.").

vision_lesson('IM-G8-U6-L18', 8, 6, 18, "Cylinder Volume").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U6-L18', teacher, "Understand the formula for volume of a cylinder (V = πr²h)").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U6-L18', teacher, "Recognize quadratic scaling: how radius changes scale volume nonlinearly").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U6-L18', teacher, "Connect geometric transformations to volume relationships").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U6-L18', student, "Explore how changes to a cylinder's radius affect its volume.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G8-U6-L18', "Students investigate the relationship between radius and volume by calculating volumes for a base cylinder and then for cylinders with scaled radii, discovering that volume depends on the square of the radius.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U6-L18', building_on, '7.G.B.6').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U6-L18', addressing, '8.G.C.9').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U6-L18', building_toward, 'G-GMD.A.3').
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U6-L18', "Calculate cylinder volume with given radius and height", "80π cm³", 'part a', "53", text).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U6-L18', "Calculate cylinder volume when radius is tripled", "720π cm³", 'part b', "53", text).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U6-L18', "Calculate cylinder volume when radius is halved", "20π cm³", 'part c', "53", text).
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G8-U6-L18', "Students commonly assume volume scales proportionally with radius (expecting 3× radius to give 3× volume), but it actually scales as the square of the radius. Tripling the radius multiplies volume by 9; halving it divides volume by 4. This task surfaces that critical nonlinear relationship, which many students initially miss.").

vision_lesson('IM-G8-U7-L1', 8, 7, 1, "Exponent Review").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U7-L1', teacher, "Comprehend that repeated division by 2 is equivalent to repeated multiplication by one-half.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U7-L1', teacher, "Create an expression that represents repeated multiplication, and explain (orally) how the structure of the expression helps compare quantities.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U7-L1', student, "Let's review exponents.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G8-U7-L1', "The purpose of this lesson is to review concepts regarding whole number exponents and to introduce the base (of an exponent) as the factor that is multiplied repeatedly. In a previous course, students learned that an exponent tells how many factors of the base to multiply. In this lesson, students make sense of problems presented in a new way. They are introduced to the idea that repeated division by a number can be thought of as repeated multiplication by the reciprocal of that number, which plays a key role in later work with negative exponents.").
