vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G8-U7-L2', "Students often multiply exponents instead of adding them (thinking 10^3 · 10^4 = 10^12). The critical move is helping them see that exponents count repeated factors: two factors of 10 times three factors of 10 gives five total factors, not six. The visual base-ten grid in Activity 2.2 grounds this before moving to purely symbolic reasoning and pattern recognition.").

vision_lesson('IM-G8-U7-L3', 8, 7, 3, "Powers of Powers of 10").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U7-L3', teacher, "Generalize a process for finding a power raised to a power, and justify (orally and in writing) that (10^n)^m = 10^(n·m)").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U7-L3', teacher, "Explain and use a rule for raising a power of 10 to a power").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U7-L3', student, "Let's look at powers of powers of 10.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G8-U7-L3', "In this lesson, students make use of repeated reasoning to discover the exponent rule (10^n)^m = 10^(n·m). Students begin by computing the volume of a very large cube. Next, they expand expressions written as a value with an exponent raised to another power and notice patterns when asked to write the expression using a single power of 10 (MP8). Students will extend this exponent rule to cases where the exponents are zero or negative in following lessons, but the focus here is on cases with positive exponents.").
