vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G8-U7-L4', "This lesson develops the quotient rule for exponents (10^n ÷ 10^m = 10^(n−m)) through systematic expansion and factor cancellation. The most common student error is interpreting 10^0 as 'zero factors' (hence 0) rather than understanding it as the multiplicative identity (1) that makes the exponent rules consistent across all cases.").

vision_lesson('IM-G8-U7-L5', 8, 7, 5, "Negative Exponents with Powers of 10").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U7-L5', teacher, "Describe (orally and in writing) how exponent rules extend to expressions involving negative exponents.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U7-L5', teacher, "Describe patterns in repeated multiplication and division with 10 and 1/10, and justify that 10^-n = 1/10^n.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U7-L5', student, "Let's see what happens when exponents are negative.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G8-U7-L5', "In this lesson, students make sense of the rule that 10^-n = 1/10^n and extend the rules they have developed for working with exponents to include situations with negative exponents. Students develop their fluency as they mentally determine missing values from equations involving powers of 10. By examining a table showing decimal, fraction, and exponential representations, students observe patterns in how the multiplier changes to increase or decrease the exponent by 1. Students correspond powers of 10 with negative exponents to repeated multiplication by 1/10. Students reinforce this understanding by matching expressions written with negative exponents to corresponding expressions written using repeated multiplication.").
