vision_lesson('IM-G8-U7-L8', 8, 7, 8, "More Exponent Rules").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U7-L8', teacher, "Use exponent rules to generate equivalent numerical expressions for expressions with different bases and bases other than 10.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U7-L8', student, "Apply exponent rules to create equivalent expressions with bases other than 10.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G8-U7-L8', "Work in this section extends students' understanding of exponents with a base of 10 to exponents with other bases. Students notice that the same rules previously determined for powers of 10 also hold for other bases, as long as the bases in a single expression are the same. Students investigate operations with expressions that contain different bases and come to generalize the rule that a^n · b^n = (a · b)^n.").
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U7-L8', "apply_product_rule_rewrite_expression", "28⁵", 'Section B Checkpoint, problem 2', "90", text).
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G8-U7-L8', "This lesson generalizes the product rule a^n · b^n = (a·b)^n to bases other than 10 through expansion and regrouping. Students routinely misunderstand that this rule requires identical exponents; they attempt to combine expressions like 3⁴ · 8³ into a single power, not recognizing the unequal exponents prevent simplification.").

vision_lesson('IM-G8-U7-L9', 8, 7, 9, "Describing Large and Small Numbers Using Powers of 10").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U7-L9', teacher, "Describe (orally and in writing) large and small numbers as multiples of powers of 10.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U7-L9', teacher, "Interpret a diagram for base-ten units, and explain (orally) how the small squares, long rectangles, and large squares relate to each other.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U7-L9', student, "Let's find out how to use powers of 10 to write large or small numbers.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G8-U7-L9', "In this lesson, students build on work done in previous grades with numbers in base ten. They use base-ten diagrams to represent different powers of 10 and review how multiplying and dividing by 10 affect the decimal representation of numbers. They use their understanding of base-ten structure as they express very large and small numbers using exponents. Students also practice communicating—by describing and writing—very large and small numbers, which requires attending to precision. This leads to a discussion about how powers of 10 can be used to more easily communicate such numbers. The focus is on introducing the idea that numbers can be written as a multiple of a power of 10 and practicing doing that flexibly.").
