vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G8-U7-L9', "This lesson is fundamentally about using place-value structure to express magnitude flexibly. The critical challenge: the same base-ten diagram represents vastly different quantities (from millionths to hundreds of millions) depending on what unit value is assigned to each small square. Students must recognize that negative exponents represent fractions (10^-3 = 1/1000), not negative magnitudes. Common errors involve miscounting zeros when converting between decimal and power notation, and misinterpreting how changing the unit changes the entire expression and its value.").

