vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G8-U7-L12', "This lesson is fundamentally about mathematical modeling with large numbers: identifying what information is necessary to answer a question, then using exponent rules and properties of powers of 10 to make otherwise unwieldy calculations tractable. A persistent misconception is treating powers of 10 as mere notational shorthand rather than understanding the structural equivalence—that (6 × 10³) × (8 × 10⁵) works because 6 × 8 = 48 and 10³ × 10⁵ = 10⁸ as separate, manipulable objects. Students also frequently include irrelevant information or omit essential context when modeling real-world situ").

