vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G8-U8-L1', "The central challenge is that students often misidentify the side length of a tilted square by reading adjacent grid units without accounting for the diagonal tilt. The surround-and-subtract strategy (enclose the tilted square in an axis-aligned square, subtract the four corner triangles) is more reliable than trying to count diagonal units directly. Students must grasp that the area formula A = s² still holds for tilted squares even when s is not aligned to the grid, preparing them for the Pythagorean theorem in later lessons.").

vision_lesson('IM-G8-U8-L2', 8, 8, 2, "Side Lengths and Areas").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U8-L2', teacher, "Comprehend the term \"square root of n\" (in spoken language) and the notation √n (in written language) to mean the side length of a square whose area is n square units.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U8-L2', teacher, "Estimate the side length of a square by comparing it to squares with known areas, and explain (orally) the reasoning.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U8-L2', student, "Let's investigate some more squares.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G8-U8-L2', "Students are formally introduced to square roots and square root notation. They begin by finding areas and side lengths of squares on a grid with whole number dimensions, reasoning that two squares with the same area must have the same side length. They then investigate squares whose side lengths are not whole numbers, using comparison to known squares to estimate unknown side lengths. Finally, they work with a geometric construction on a coordinate plane, where rotating a square about the origin reveals its side length as a point on the number line, leading to the introduction of square root notation.").
