vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U8-L16', teacher, "Enable students to write fractions as repeating decimals using long division and repeated reasoning.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U8-L16', student, "Let's learn more about how rational numbers can be represented.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G8-U8-L16', "This lesson explores different representations of rational numbers by helping students see that the same rational number can be written as a fraction, a decimal, or even as roots. Through zooming number lines and long division, students discover that some rationals have terminating decimal expansions (like 3/8 = 0.375) while others have repeating patterns (like 2/11 = 0.1818...). Both types are called rational numbers because any rational number can eventually be expressed as a positive or negative fraction a/b where a and b are integers with b ≠ 0.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U8-L16', building_on, '7.NS.A.2.d').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U8-L16', addressing, '8.EE.A').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U8-L16', addressing, '8.NS.A').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U8-L16', addressing, '8.NS.A.1').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U8-L16', building_toward, '8.NS.A').
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U8-L16', "fraction_to_decimal_conversion", "0.375", 'Activity 16.3: Rational Numbers as Decim', "228-229", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U8-L16', "repeating_decimal_long_division", "0.1818... (repeating)", 'Activity 16.4: Zooming In on 2/11', "230-233", figure).
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G8-U8-L16', "The core insight is that rational numbers exist in multiple representations—fraction, terminating decimal, or repeating decimal—but students often conflate the place-value structure of decimals with the equal-parts partition structure of fractions. A major pitfall: students may not understand why 3/8 terminates (denominator has only factors of 2 and 5) but 2/11 repeats forever, nor why a repeating decimal like 0.1̄8̄ is still rational. The zooming number lines are essential here—they help students visualize that 2/11 gets closer and closer to precise tick marks but never lands exactly, creatin").

vision_lesson('IM-G8-U8-L17', 8, 8, 17, "Infinite Decimal Expansions").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U8-L17', teacher, "Compare and contrast (orally) decimal expansions for rational and irrational numbers.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U8-L17', teacher, "Coordinate (orally and in writing) repeating decimal expansions and rational numbers that represent the same number.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U8-L17', student, "Let's think about infinite decimals.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G8-U8-L17', "In this lesson, students explore finding decimal expansions of rational numbers as well as irrational numbers. Students begin by using long division to find the decimal expansion of 3/7, which starts to repeat after the seventh decimal place. Repeated reasoning allows students to stop the long division process and express the decimal expansion following the same steps (MP8). Next, students learn how to take a repeating decimal expansion and rewrite it in fraction form by ordering a set of cards that show the steps and an explanation of the process. They then practice with different decimal expansions following the same steps (MP7). In the last activity of this lesson, students investigate how to approximate decimal expansions of irrational numbers. Since values like √2 and π cannot be written as a fraction, students use successive approximations to find more and more digits of their decimal expansions.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U8-L17', building_on, '7.NS.A.2.d').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U8-L17', building_on, '8.EE.C.7.b').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U8-L17', addressing, '8.NS.A.1').
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U8-L17', "long_division_repeating_decimal", "5714", 'Activity 17.1, Student Task Statement', "240", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U8-L17', "repeating_decimal_to_fraction", "441/990", 'Activity 17.2, Student Task Statement', "241", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U8-L17', "repeating_decimal_to_fraction", "185/990", 'Activity 17.2, part 2.a', "242", text).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U8-L17', "repeating_decimal_to_fraction", "71/90", 'Activity 17.2, part 2.b', "242", text).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U8-L17', "approximate_irrational_successive_approximation", "1.414", 'Activity 17.3, parts 1.a–1.d', "244", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U8-L17', "approximate_irrational_from_measurement", "≈3.14", 'Activity 17.3, part 2', "244", text).
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G8-U8-L17', "This lesson distinguishes rational numbers (with terminating or repeating decimal expansions) from irrational numbers (with non-repeating, non-terminating expansions). Students often misunderstand why 0.999... equals 1 exactly, and struggle to see why the algebraic method of converting repeating decimals to fractions—multiplying by powers of 10, then subtracting to isolate the repeating block—actually works: the machinery reaches what teachers often frame as a limit or pattern recognition, but the formal justification demands facility with equation solving that the curriculum has not yet isola").

vision_lesson('IM-G8-U8-L18', 8, 8, 18, "When Is the Same Size Not the Same Size?").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U8-L18', teacher, "Apply ratios and the Pythagorean Theorem to solve a problem involving the aspect ratio of screens or photos, and explain (orally) the reasoning.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U8-L18', teacher, "Describe (in writing and using other representations) characteristics of rectangles with the same aspect ratio or with different aspect ratios.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G8-U8-L18', "In this culminating lesson for the unit, students use the Pythagorean Theorem to compare the diagonal lengths of rectangles with various dimensions. They investigate different aspect ratios of items such as photographs and smartphone screens. There is an element of mathematical modeling (MP4) in the last activity, because in order to quantify the screens' sizes to compare them, students need to refine the question that is asked.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U8-L18', building_on, '6.G.A.1').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U8-L18', building_on, '6.RP.A.1').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U8-L18', addressing, '8.G.B.7').
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U8-L18', "longer_side_from_aspect_ratio", "20 inches", 'Activity 18.2, Question 2a', "257-258", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U8-L18', "diagonal_from_sides_pythagorean", "25 inches", 'Activity 18.2, Question 2b', "257-258", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U8-L18', "sides_from_diagonal_with_aspect_ratio", "8 inches and 6 inches", 'Activity 18.2, Question 3', "257-258", text).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U8-L18', "sides_from_diagonal_with_aspect_ratio", "4.8 inches and 3.6 inches", 'Activity 18.2, Question 4', "257-258", text).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U8-L18', "compare_screen_areas_different_aspect_ratios", "Yes; the new screen (18.5:9, 5.8-inch diagonal) is 1.1 square inches smaller than the old screen (16:9, 5.8-inch diagonal). Old area: 14.4 sq in; new area: 13.3 sq in.", 'Activity 18.3, Main Problem', "259-261", figure).
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G8-U8-L18', "Rectangles with the same diagonal can have different areas; aspect ratio determines screen size. Students often conflate diagonal length with \"size,\" missing that proportions dramatically affect area. The lesson requires solving multi-step equations where ratio constraints (e.g., sides as 4x and 3x) combine with the Pythagorean theorem to fix a scale factor, then comparing areas—not diagonals—to determine which screen is actually larger.").

vision_lesson('IM-G8-U9-L1', 8, 9, 1, "Tessellations of the Plane").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U9-L1', teacher, "Create and describe patterns with specific polygons that fill the plane.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U9-L1', student, "Let's explore geometric patterns!").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G8-U9-L1', "This optional lesson focuses on the idea of a tessellation: a repeating pattern that covers a plane with no gaps or overlaps. The lesson begins with a visual analysis of tessellations where students apply their knowledge of geometry and transformations to describe repeating patterns. In the next activity, students create and compare tessellations by making use of structure (MP7). Finally, students work to describe and recreate tessellations from a partner's description. As they become more precise in their descriptions, their recreations become more exact (MP6). This lesson also includes examples of tessellations used in art from a variety of cultures, which can be explored as an extension.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U9-L1', building_on, '7.G.A').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U9-L1', addressing, '8.G.A').
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G8-U9-L1', "A tessellation tiles a plane with no gaps or overlaps; the key constraint is that certain shapes (like regular hexagons) force a unique pattern because exactly three must meet at each vertex, while other shapes offer multiple tessellation possibilities. Students often conflate \"describing a tessellation\" with \"knowing its geometric properties\"—precision in specifying placement and transformations (translations by direction-distance, rotations by center-and-angle, reflections by line) is the cognitive work, not numerical computation.").

vision_lesson('IM-G8-U9-L2', 8, 9, 2, "Regular Tessellations").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U9-L2', teacher, "Justify (orally and in writing) that regular triangles, squares, and hexagons are the only regular polygons that can be used to create a regular tessellation.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U9-L2', student, "Let's make some regular tessellations.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G8-U9-L2', "In this second lesson in the sequence of three optional lessons, students look at regular tessellations, which are made of regular polygons. Students construct arguments about which regular polygons can create regular tessellations (MP3) and reason about why others cannot (MP2). This reasoning requires an understanding of the structure of interior angles of regular polygons (MP7). Through the lesson, students show in detail that triangles, squares, and hexagons give the only possible regular tessellations. Students begin by exploring triangles, squares, pentagons, hexagons, and octagons to determine which can create a regular tessellation. Then students focus on equilateral triangles and the angle measurements that guarantee equilateral triangles will tessellate. Finally, students experiment with shapes that have more sides to determine if any of those can create regular tessellations, bringing in their knowledge of angle measures to support their claims.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U9-L2', building_on, '7.G.B').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U9-L2', addressing, '8.G.A').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U9-L2', addressing, '8.G.A.5').
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U9-L2', "equilateral_triangle_interior_angle", "60", 'Activity 2.2, Task 1 (Student Response)', "17", text).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U9-L2', "triangles_at_vertex", "6", 'Activity 2.2, Task 2 (Student Response)', "17", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U9-L2', "vertex_angle_sum_triangles", "360", 'Activity 2.2, Task 2 (Student Response)', "17", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U9-L2', "squares_at_vertex", "4", 'Activity 2.1, Task 1 (Student Response)', "15", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U9-L2', "hexagons_at_vertex", "3", 'Activity 2.1, Task 1 (Student Response)', "15", figure).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U9-L2', "square_interior_angle", "90", 'Activity 2.3, Task 2 (Student Response)', "20", text).
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G8-U9-L2', "The lesson hinges on a deceptively simple constraint: a regular tessellation works only when a whole number of polygons fit exactly at each vertex with their interior angles summing to 360°. Students often underestimate how restrictive this angle-sum requirement is and may not understand why a 'perfect' regular pentagon fails despite being a valid regular shape—they confuse regularity with tessellability.").

vision_lesson('IM-G8-U9-L3', 8, 9, 3, "Tessellating Polygons").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U9-L3', teacher, "Generalize (orally) that any triangle or quadrilateral can be used to tessellate the plane.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U9-L3', student, "Let's make tessellations with different polygons.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G8-U9-L3', "In this third in the sequence of three optional lessons, students examine tessellations using non-regular polygons. Students first study triangles and show that any triangle can tessellate the plane by composing two copies into a parallelogram (a grade 6 idea revisited). Next, students show that all quadrilaterals can also tessellate the plane by using rigid motions and the fact that the sum of the angles in a quadrilateral is always 360 degrees. Lastly, students investigate a pentagon whose tessellation leads to rotational thinking. Through experimenting with these shapes, students construct arguments about which polygons can tessellate the plane and why (MP3) and apply their knowledge of interior angles of polygons to support their arguments (MP7).").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U9-L3', addressing, '8.G.A').
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G8-U9-L3', "Students often believe only regular or symmetric polygons can tessellate; this lesson proves that any triangle or quadrilateral works because their interior angles sum perfectly to fill vertices (180° and 360° respectively). The key misconception students face is not recognizing how angle arithmetic forces the tessellation pattern, and assuming all pentagons tessellate once they discover some do.").

vision_lesson('IM-G8-U9-L4', 8, 9, 4, "What Influences Temperature?").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U9-L4', teacher, "Create a plan to model a relationship involving bivariate data.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U9-L4', student, "Let's see if we can predict the temperature.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G8-U9-L4', "In this optional lesson, students investigate how to predict the temperature of a location in North America. This question is purposefully vague and is meant for students to think critically about the variables needed to model the situation with mathematics.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U9-L4', addressing, '8.F.A.1').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U9-L4', addressing, '8.F.B').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U9-L4', addressing, '8.SP.A').
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G8-U9-L4', "This lesson introduces the modeling cycle by establishing that temperature depends on multiple variables, so students must strategically fix some (time, geographic scope) while investigating others (latitude). The key misconception: students often expect a clean functional relationship without recognizing that confounders like elevation and ocean proximity create real-world messiness that violates the function definition.").

vision_lesson('IM-G8-U9-L5', 8, 9, 5, "Plotting the Temperature").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U9-L5', teacher, "Create a mathematical model of bivariate data using a scatter plot.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U9-L5', student, "Let's construct a model.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G8-U9-L5', "In this second in the sequence of optional lessons, students construct a mathematical model to investigate if there is an association between latitude and temperature (MP4). The lesson begins with an example of a scatter plot and how to talk about associations seen in data. Then students create and answer questions about the data they gathered or the data provided in the lesson. In either case, students create a scatter plot of the data and approximate a line of best fit. They must make decisions about reasonable values when creating their axes and interpreting the data (MP2).").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U9-L5', addressing, '8.SP.A').
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U9-L5', "latitude_range_identification", "minimum 12.36 degrees north (Chinandega, NI), maximum 64.84 degrees north (Fairbanks, AK)", 'Activity 5.2, Question 2', "39", text).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U9-L5', "temperature_range_identification", "minimum 50 degrees Fahrenheit (Yellowknife, NT), maximum 96 degrees Fahrenheit (Tucson, AZ)", 'Activity 5.2, Question 2', "39", text).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U9-L5', "scatter_plot_construction", "24 ordered pairs (latitude, temperature) plotted with latitude in degrees north on x-axis and temperature in Fahrenheit on y-axis", 'Activity 5.3, Task 1', "41", text).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U9-L5', "linear_equation_approximation", "y = -0.87x + 111, where x is latitude and y is temperature", 'Activity 5.3, Task 3', "41", figure).
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G8-U9-L5', "Students model the negative association between latitude and temperature using scatter plots and lines of best fit. The key challenge is understanding that the line of best fit is an approximation—students need to accept that different groups' eyeball estimates will vary slightly and that choosing appropriate axis scales based on data range often requires explicit scaffolding.").

vision_lesson('IM-G8-U9-L6', 8, 9, 6, "Using and Interpreting a Mathematical Model").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U9-L6', teacher, "Interpret a scatter plot and line of fit that model temperature and latitude, and explain (orally) limitations of the model.").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U9-L6', teacher, "Use a mathematical model of bivariate data to make predictions (in writing).").
vision_lesson_goal('IM-G8-U9-L6', student, "Let's use a model to make some predictions.").
vision_lesson_purpose('IM-G8-U9-L6', "To complete this section, in this optional lesson students analyze their model and use it to make predictions and draw conclusions. Students validate their model by seeing how well it predicts the actual temperature for locations that were not included in the original data. They also look for and investigate outliers in the data. Finally, students interpret mathematical features of their model (slope and intercepts of the line) and discuss limitations of the model.").
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U9-L6', addressing, '8.F.B').
vision_lesson_standard('IM-G8-U9-L6', addressing, '8.SP.A').
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U9-L6', "evaluate_linear_model_detroit", "74.2 degrees Fahrenheit", 'Activity 6.1, Question 1a', "43-44", text).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U9-L6', "evaluate_linear_model_albuquerque", "80.5 degrees Fahrenheit", 'Activity 6.1, Question 1b', "43-44", text).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U9-L6', "evaluate_linear_model_nome", "54.9 degrees Fahrenheit", 'Activity 6.1, Question 1c', "43-44", text).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U9-L6', "find_vertical_intercept", "111 degrees Fahrenheit", 'Activity 6.2, Question 2', "46", text).
vision_lesson_computation('IM-G8-U9-L6', "find_horizontal_intercept", "Over 100 degrees north (physically nonexistent)", 'Activity 6.2, Question 2', "46", text).
vision_lesson_boundary('IM-G8-U9-L6', "This lesson teaches that a mathematically valid model has real-world limitations tied to the data it was built from. Students often assume an equation that works mathematically will predict accurately at all values of the independent variable; they struggle to recognize that predictions at extreme latitudes are unreliable and that geographic-specific climate patterns constrain the model's domain to North America alone.").

%!  vision_lessons_for_standard(+CCSS, -Codes) is det.
%   Every extracted lesson that works on a Common Core standard (any band).
vision_lessons_for_standard(CCSS, Codes) :-
    findall(Code, vision_lesson_standard(Code, _Band, CCSS), Codes0),
    sort(Codes0, Codes).

%!  vision_lesson_digest_summary(+Code, -Summary) is semidet.
%   A compact teacher-facing dict for one lesson.
vision_lesson_digest_summary(Code, Summary) :-
    vision_lesson(Code, G, U, L, Title),
    findall(T, vision_lesson_goal(Code, teacher, T), Goals),
    ( vision_lesson_purpose(Code, P) -> Purpose = P ; Purpose = "" ),
    findall(S-C, vision_lesson_standard(Code, S, C), Stds),
    findall(Task-Ans, vision_lesson_computation(Code, Task, Ans, _, _, _), Comps),
    findall(F-W, vision_lesson_error(Code, F, W, _), Errors),
    ( vision_lesson_boundary(Code, B) -> Boundary = B ; Boundary = none ),
    Summary = digest{code:Code, grade:G, unit:U, lesson:L, title:Title,
                     goals:Goals, purpose:Purpose, standards:Stds,
                     computations:Comps, anticipated_errors:Errors,
                     boundary:Boundary}.
